<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Pilot of Downed U.S. Jet Rescued  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon said  
the unidentified pilot from a U.S. stealth fighter lost over 
Yugoslavia tonight had been rescued and was safe at an ``allied air 
force base.'' He said the cause of the crash wasn't known and 
refused to provide details of the rescue. The downed plane was the 
alliance's first loss in the four-day air campaign to prevent 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic from carrying out ``ethnic 
cleansing'' in separatist Kosovo province. Television stations in 
the Yugoslav capital broadcast footage showing flames rising from a 
tangled wreck that bore U.S. Air Force markings and the words ``Air 
Combat Command.'' The official Tanjug news agency said the 
radar-evading F-117 fighter was shot down 9 p.m. local time near 
Budjenovci, 35 miles northwest of Belgrade. 

</P>
<P>
	Savage Killings Reported in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	MORINI, Albania (AP) -- As thousands of ethnic Albanians fled  
Kosovo today, Western officials said there were unconfirmed reports 
of a savage new campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' that has escalated 
dramatically since NATO attacks began. Ethnic Albanian sources 
remaining in the Serbian province made allegations of killing, 
kidnapping, and looting by paramilitary gangs, some targeting 
civilians in door-to-door raids. Across the Albanian border, a line 
of refugees stretched for a mile watched by about 10 Yugoslav army 
soldiers holding machine guns. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Protests Staged Across Europe  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Protests against NATO airstrikes on Yugoslavia  
drew thousands of demonstrators today in cities throughout Europe 
as alliance missiles and warplanes again pounded the Balkan nation. 
In Russia, about 2,000 protesters staged rallies outside the 
American and British embassies in Moscow. In Ukraine, 
demonstrations continued as two government ministers traveled to 
Belgrade to offer mediation in possible peace talks. In Vienna, 
Austria, more than 4,000 protesters gathered in front of the U.S. 
Embassy, shouting ``Viva Serbia.'' There were also protests in 
Norway, Romania, Cyprus, the Czech Republic and other countries. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Said To Have Raised $3 Million  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seeking an early edge in a crowded GOP field,  
Texas Gov. George W. Bush has raised at least $3 million so far 
this year for a possible presidential bid, according to Republicans 
familiar with his fund raising. Bush's take for the first three 
months of 1999 is expected to put him ahead of several potential 
rivals for the Republican presidential nomination when their first 
fund-raising reports come out April 15. The race for campaign funds 
is considered the first primary of the 2000 presidential election. 
Politicians and strategists say a candidate needs to raise $20 
million by the end of this year to properly finance a campaign in 
2000. 

</P>
<P>
	Leaders Appeal for N. Ireland Pact  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The British and Irish prime  
ministers, Tony Blair and Bertie Ahern, made a joint newspaper 
appeal Sunday for Northern Ireland's politicians to overcome their 
suspicions and form a coalition government this week. ``Both of us 
stand ready to meet the parties to devise a way out of the current 
impasse,'' Blair and Ahern wrote in The Observer. Ahern and Blair 
are expected to arrive together early next week in Belfast to 
supervise shuttle diplomacy among party delegations. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Visits Tunisia, Morocco  
</P>
<P>
	TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton met for more than  
an hour today with Tunisian President Zine El Abidine Ben Ali, who 
assured the first lady human rights problems ``will be properly 
addressed,'' an administration official said. From Tunis, Mrs. 
Clinton headed to Morocco, where she visited a school in rural Er 
Rachidia and announced a $1.6 million U.S. grant to help Moroccan 
schools educate girls. 

</P>
<P>
	Experts Warn of Computer Virus  
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A new computer virus can allow documents to be  
e-mailed to other people without warning, a potential security 
breach that should worry businesses and governments, an expert at 
Carnegie Mellon University said today. The ``Melissa macro'' or 
W97M--Melissa virus spreads via infected e-mail and attacks 
computers loaded with Microsoft's widely used Word 97 or Word 2000 
programs, according to CERT -- or Computer Emergency Response Team -- 
Carnegie Mellon's Department of Defense-funded computer security 
team. 

</P>
<P>
	Duke, UConn Advance to NCAA Final  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Top-ranked Duke defeated Michigan  
State 68-62 tonight and advanced to the NCAA finals against 
Connecticut. Elton Brand dominated with 17 points and 14 rebounds, 
but he picked up his fourth foul with 10:12 left on a charge drawn 
by Mateen Cleaves in the open court. Guards Trajan Langdon and 
William Avery sandwiched 3-pointers around a layup by Michigan 
State's Morris Peterson and then Avery's drive with 6:14 to play 
had Duke's lead at 59-50. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  

</P>
</TEXT>
