<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fraschilla Named New Mexico Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Brooklyn-born Fran Fraschilla will  
finally get to go West as the next coach at New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Fired last year at St. John's after developing an interest in  
the coaching vacancy at Arizona State, Fraschilla was hired 
Saturday by the Lobos. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a basketball junkie and the chance to coach in one of the  
best environments in college basketball is just a dream come 
through,'' Fraschilla said during a telephone conference call from 
the Final Four in St. Petersburg. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraschilla, 40, has been a frequent shopper for coaching  
vacancies throughout the country in recent months. His name has 
surfaced in coaching job openings at Georgia, San Diego State, 
Pittsburgh, East Carolina and Southwest Missouri State. 
</P>
<P>
	His hiring at New Mexico came four days after Dave Bliss  
resigned to take the head coaching job at Baylor. 
</P>
<P>
	New Mexico athletic director Rudy Davalos called Fraschilla  
``one of the best recruiters in the country,'' and a coach with the 
ability to take the Lobos to a higher level of national prominence. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is I want the best for New Mexico  
basketball,'' Davalos said. ``I'm excited as heck about a guy that 
can give us a different aspect. The guy I hired is a high, high, 
high energy coach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Associate athletic director Bill McGillis, a member of the  
advisory committee that helped in the search, said Fraschilla was 
the leading candidate from the start on a list that started out 
long and was trimmed to about six candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once Bliss started looking at the Saint Louis and Baylor jobs,  
we came up with a list,'' McGillis said. ``Fran was always at the 
top. He has a national profile and the focus was always on him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bliss left as the winningest coach in New Mexico history with a  
record of 246-108 in 11 seasons. He led the Lobos to seven NCAA 
tournaments in the last nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	New Mexico was 25-9 this season and lost to Connecticut at the  
West Regional. In Bliss' final four seasons, the Lobos won 102 
games, but Bliss became the target of increasing criticism from 
fans and the media for the Lobos' inability to advance further than 
the second round of the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraschilla, who coached St. John's to its first NCAA tournament  
bid since 1993, said he was ready for the mania and fish bowl 
atmosphere in Albuquerque, where the Lobos are the only game in 
town and annually rank among the top 10 schools nationally in home 
attendance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy to be going into a place where people expect you to  
win,'' Fraschilla said. ``Coming from New York, I'm used to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Fraschilla left St. John's, the school said it had reached  
an agreement with Fraschilla to end their relationship because of 
``fundamental differences over the management of the basketball 
program.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The school said the decision had nothing to do with any unlawful  
conduct, violations of NCAA regulations or financial improprieties, 
and that none of those things had been reported or alleged. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can say it was based on the opportunity to look at the  
Arizona State job and it ruffled some feathers back at St. 
John's,'' Fraschilla said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
