<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Rejects Adidas Logo Size Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OVERLAND PARK, Kan. (AP) -- A federal judge on Friday denied a  
bid by Adidas America Inc. to keep the NCAA from limiting the size 
of commercial logos on uniforms, the NCAA said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Portland, Ore., subsidiary of the European apparel and  
footwear company filed suit last Nov. 12 in U.S. District Court in 
Kansas City, Kan., saying the NCAA's bylaw on commercial logos 
violated antitrust laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The bylaw restricts member schools to selling space for only a  
single manufacturer's logo or mark on apparel and limits it to 2 1/4 
square inches in area, the lawsuit said. 
</P>
<P>
	Adidas' logo consists of three parallel stripes down the arms  
and legs of apparel and won't fit in the area set out by the rule. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Thomas Van Bebber on Friday denied the  
company's motion for a preliminary injunction. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a news release Friday night from the NCAA, the  
judge said in his order that Adidas had failed to show there was a 
likelihood it would eventually win on the merits of its claim, or 
that it faced irreparable harm without a preliminary injuction. 
</P>
<P>
	Telephone calls to Adidas America Inc.'s headquarters in  
Beaverton, Ore., seeking comment were unanswered Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Bebber said the bylaw was not subject to antitrust laws  
because it ``has neither the purpose nor the effect of giving the 
NCAA or its member institutions an advantage in any commercial 
transaction,'' the NCAA said, quoting from the judge's order. 
</P>
<P>
	Further, the judge said, the bylaw supports the NCAA's principle  
of maintaining amateurism in intercollegiate sports ``by preventing 
member schools from turning their student-athletes into billboards 
in the pursuit of advertising revenues,'' according to the NCAA 
release. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge also noted that the bylaw helps avoid advertising that  
could interfere with the function of uniforms in identifying 
players to teammates and referees. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsa Cole, general counsel for the NCAA, said the regulatory  
body for college athletics was pleased by the ruling, especially 
Van Bebber's finding that antitrust laws do not apply to the logo 
bylaw. 
</P>
<P>
	Adidas and other manufacturers spend millions of dollars a year  
on sponsorship agreements with top college teams and coaches. They 
get players to wear their merchandise as a way of generating demand 
for their shoes, apparel and equipment, Adidas had said in the 
lawsuit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
