<HEADLINE> Imus Water Plan Faces Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) -- Don Imus has encountered a wave of  
opposition over water use at his proposed ranch for sick children. 
</P>
<P>
	The nationally syndicated radio personality has raised millions  
of dollars for the children's ranch, which he hopes to open this 
summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Imus' water plans call for pumping up to 100 acre-feet of water  
per year from four proposed 900-foot-deep wells. One acre-foot, the 
amount needed to cover an acre a foot deep, is about 326,000 
gallons. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're concerned about the impact on the wells around here of  
any deep pumping,'' said Nicasio Romero, a commissioner on the El 
Ancon Acequia, an irrigation association. 
</P>
<P>
	``For something like this even to be proposed is ridiculous,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Imus has declined to discuss the project, and there was no  
answer Friday at his New York office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990327.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 16:51:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Soccer Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Raul Gonzalez scored four times as Spain routed Austria 9-0  
Saturday in qualifying for next year's European Championship, and 
Italy, England and Germany also gained key wins. 
</P>
<P>
	At Valencia, Gonzalez scored in the sixth, 18th, 47th and 73rd  
minutes, leading Spain (2-1) in the debut of coach Jose Antonio 
Camacho. Cyprus (3-1) leads Group Six, with Austria (2-1-1) second 
and Spain third. 
</P>
<P>
	On a day when 15 qualifiers were played, England beat Poland 3-1  
at Wembley in its first game under coach Kevin Keegan, with Paul 
Scholes scoring three goals. Sweden (3-0) leads Group Five, 
followed by England (2-1-1) and Poland (2-1). 
</P>
<P>
	At Copenhagen, visiting Italy beat Denmark 2-1, with Antonio  
Conte scoring the go-ahead goal on a diving header in the 69th 
minute. Filippo Inzaghi had put Italy ahead in the first minute, 
but Ebbe Sand tied it in the 56th. Italy (3-0) leads Group One, 
while Denmark (0-2-2) is fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	At Belfast, visiting Germany (2-1) defeated Northern Ireland 3-0  
as Marco Bode scored twice and Dieter Hamann once. It was just the 
second win for the defending European champions since Erich Ribbeck 
replaced Berti Vogts as coach. The Germans are second to Turkey 
(3-1) in Group Three, and Northern Ireland (1-2-1) is fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	At Saint-Denis, World Cup champion France (2-0-2) was held to a  
scoreless tie by (3-0-1) Ukraine, the Group Four leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Macedonia's game against Ireland and Yugoslavia's game against  
Croatia were postponed because of NATO bombing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
