<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wrongly Convicted Woman Sues N.Y. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- A woman wrongly convicted of murder in  
1973 is seeking $12.5 million from New York state to compensate her 
for spending 25 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Betty Tyson, 50, maintains she was robbed of her freedom, her  
wages and her ability to bear children. She underwent a 
hysterectomy in prison and claims she would have gotten better 
medical treatment in a regular hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson's ``psychological injuries and her lost ability to bear  
children are permanent,'' according to a lawsuit filed earlier this 
month in the New York Court of Claims. 
</P>
<P>
	A former prostitute, Tyson was sentenced to 25 years to life in  
prison for the slaying of Philadelphia businessman Timothy Haworth, 
52, a consultant to Eastman Kodak Co. He was apparently soliciting 
a prostitute when he was strangled in an alley the night of May 25, 
1973. 
</P>
<P>
	Police had no physical evidence linking Tyson to the killing.  
She was found guilty based on a confession she said police beat out 
of her and the testimony of two teen-agers who told of seeing her 
with Haworth. 
</P>
<P>
	Her conviction was dismissed last May after a judge ruled  
evidence had been unlawfully suppressed. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, the city of Rochester agreed to pay Tyson $1.25  
million to settle a wrongful conviction lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time she was freed, Tyson had become New York's  
longest-serving female inmate. She declined Saturday to discuss the 
lawsuit. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
