<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Serb TV Reports Downed NATO Plane  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serbian television reported early  
Sunday that a NATO plane had been shot down in Yugoslavia. Footage 
showed flames rising from a tangled wreck. ``I cannot confirm it,'' 
a NATO spokesman in Brussels, Belgium, said. The Pentagon refused 
to comment. Signs of possible escalation of the Kosovo conflict 
continued. Earlier, NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said the 
stepped up assault, which he said had the approval of every 
government in the alliance, was needed ``to bring a halt to 
violence in Kosovo and prevent further humanitarian catastrophe.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Savage Killings Reported in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	MORINI, Albania (AP) -- As thousands of ethnic Albanians fled  
Kosovo today, Western officials said there were unconfirmed reports 
of a savage new campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' that has escalated 
dramatically since NATO attacks began. Ethnic Albanian sources 
remaining in the Serbian province made allegations of killing, 
kidnapping, and looting by paramilitary gangs, some targeting 
civilians in door-to-door raids. Across the Albanian border, a line 
of refugees stretched for a mile watched by about 10 Yugoslav army 
soldiers holding machine guns. 

</P>
<P>
	Polls: U.S. Divided on Airstrikes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New polls show that Americans are closely  
divided on NATO airstrikes against Yugoslavia. Support for U.S. 
involvement in the air campaign stood at 53 percent in a Newsweek 
poll taken during the second and third days of the bombing, which 
began Wednesday. Thirty-six percent opposed it. A Time-CNN poll 
found 44 percent approving of the action and 40 percent against it. 

</P>
<P>
	Ten Wounded in Kurd Suicide Bombing  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- A woman set off hand grenades strapped  
to her body and stuffed in her backpack when stopped by police in 
Istanbul's main square today, killing herself and wounding 10 
others. There was no immediate claim of responsibility, but 
authorities accused Kurdish rebels seeking revenge for the recent 
arrest and imprisonment of their leader, Abdullah Ocalan. A day 
earlier, a previously unknown group calling itself the Nationalist 
Kurdish Revenge Forces threatened attacks in a statement carried by 
a pro-Kurdish news agency in Germany. 

</P>
<P>
	Four Killed in Paraguay Protests  
</P>
<P>
	ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- Hundreds of troops forced apart rival  
demonstrators outside Paraguay's congress building today and 
lawmakers resumed the president's impeachment trial after a night 
of deadly clashes. Many legislators were seen entering congress 
wearing bulletproof vests, and some blamed President Raul Cubas' 
government for failing to quell hours of flare-ups yesterday and 
early today that left at least four people dead. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Meets Tunisian President  
</P>
<P>
	TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton met for more than  
an hour today with Tunisian President Zine El Abidine Ben Ali, who 
assured the first lady human rights problems ``will be properly 
addressed,'' an administration official said. According to a U.S. 
official, Ben Ali acknowledged ``shortcomings'' in his government's 
record on political freedoms but said a tight rein on dissidents in 
Tunisia helps keep Islamic extremists from making inroads from 
neighboring Algeria and Libya. From Tunis, Mrs. Clinton headed to 
Morocco, where she visited a school in rural Er Rachidia and 
announced a $1.6 million U.S. grant to help Moroccan schools 
educate girls. 

</P>
<P>
	Computer Virus Warning Issued  
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A new computer virus can allow documents to be  
e-mailed to other people without warning, a potential security 
breach that should worry businesses and governments, an expert at 
Carnegie Mellon University said today. The ``Melissa macro'' or 
W97M--Melissa virus spreads via infected e-mail and attacks 
computers loaded with Microsoft's widely used Word 97 or Word 2000 
programs, according to CERT -- or Computer Emergency Response Team -- 
Carnegie Mellon's Department of Defense-funded computer security 
team. 

</P>
<P>
	Penn Bans Alcohol at Campus Parties  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The University of Pennsylvania has banned  
alcohol at undergraduate campus parties after a partygoer died at a 
fraternity house. The ban, expected to last at least until a 
student-faculty task force at the Ivy League school takes up the 
issue in about six weeks, applies to registered campus parties, 
typically those hosted by fraternities and attended by nonmembers. 

</P>
<P>
	Richard Krajicek Wins Lipton Title  
</P>
<P>
	KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. (AP) -- Richard Krajicek won his first U.S.  
tournament title since 1993 today, dealing 24 aces to beat unseeded 
Frenchman Sebastien Grosjean 4-6, 6-1, 6-2, 7-5 in the final of the 
Lipton Championships. The women's title will be decided in a 
sibling showdown tomorrow between Venus and Serena Williams. It's 
the first all-sister women's final since the Open era began in 
1968. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  

</P>
