<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 17:12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Players Championship Notebook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Three days ago, Skip Kendall  
needed help getting out of bed. 
</P>
<P>
	His wife, Beth, had to help him put his socks on. She started  
teasing him, saying their nine-month-old son Noah could get around 
better than he could. 
</P>
<P>
	So while everybody else complained about the weather Saturday at  
The Players Championship, Kendall was simply happy to be playing -- 
then contending. 
</P>
<P>
	Kendall overcame a bad back to shoot a 2-under-par 70 to finish  
at 3-under-par 213, just two strokes back of David Duval after 
three rounds at the windswept Tournament Players Club at Sawgrass. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm thinking more about if I can play the next day rather than  
where I am in the tournament,'' said Kendall, who is seeking his 
first career PGA tournament victory. ``Maybe that is a blessing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The trouble began at the first practice hole Wednesday, when he  
bent over to pluck his ball out of the hole. He wrenched his back, 
could barely walk and quit the round before even getting to the No. 
2 tee box. 
</P>
<P>
	After an evening of intense therapy, he practically crawled out  
of bed and decided to head out to the course to see if he could 
play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Billy Ray Brown, the first alternate, he was watching me like  
a hawk,'' Kendall said. ``But it loosened up enough to where it 
hasn't really affected me on the golf course.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His first two rounds of 70 and 73 were barely notable. But when  
the wind kicked up and the field tightened, Kendall was there to 
take advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	With all the troubles involving heavy winds, thick roughs and  
slick greens, Kendall said it was almost a relief to have another 
distraction, the nagging pain, to keep him occupied. 
</P>
<P>
	``It hurts more when I miss-hit because when you kind of clank  
it, the vibration goes up the shaft,'' he said. ``It makes me work 
harder on hitting it solid.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	TERRIBLE TWOSOME:@ Davis Love III played 16 holes well. The  
other two were complete disasters. 
</P>
<P>
	His playing partner, Bruce Lietzke, left the course envying the  
day Love had. 
</P>
<P>
	It was one of those rounds -- with no help from the weather, of  
course -- for the twosome playing behind the lead group of Duval and 
Joe Ozaki. 
</P>
<P>
	Love had a pair of 7s, a triple bogey on the par-4 first and a  
quad on the par-3 17th island hole, to finish the day at 6-over 78 
and 2-over for the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was two holes, I made two 7s, that says it all,'' Love  
said. ``It was one of the worst days of golf on this course that 
I've ever seen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lietzke's day was even worse, although maybe less dramatic.  
</P>
<P>
	He three-putted No. 1. He missed 5-foot putts to save par on  
Nos. 3 and 5. He started at 5-under and shot 8-over par 80 to join 
Love in falling from the second group on Saturday to anonymity 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``With both me and Davis, some of it was self-inflicted,''  
Lietzke said. ``But some of it was well-struck golf shots that 
ended up in places where it was impossible to recover.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	JOE'S BAD DAY:@ Ozaki also melted down, shooting a 9-over 81 to  
fall from the lead into a five-way tie for 20th at 2 over. 
</P>
<P>
	It was reminiscent of last year, when he held the lead after two  
rounds and sunk to 18th place by the finish. 
</P>
<P>
	Ozaki, who speaks little English, fielded questions through  
translator Robert Turner. When a reporter asked if thoughts of last 
year crept into Ozaki's mind, Turner refused to relay the question. 
</P>
<P>
	The discussion then turned to the conditions and the double  
bogey Ozaki had to open the round, immediately dropping him behind 
Duval for the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was tough getting control of my emotions,'' Ozaki said  
through the translator. ``Then, it was hard to maneuver the ball. 
You put it all together and it was a bad day.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	PHIL'S ODDITY:@ The winds dried out the greens and subjected  
Phil Mickelson to something he had never seen before. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the first hole, I had a putt that was just trickling up,  
just going by the hole,'' he said. ``It hit a spike mark and came 
backwards. That was when I knew it was going to be a long day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mickelson was one of the survivors, however. He shot 1-under 71  
to finish at 3-under, tied with Kendall for second place. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	NOT FRIENDLY:@ Things were so bad for Bob Friend that he left  
the course not knowing what he shot. 
</P>
<P>
	For the record, it was a 15-over 87, ruining a good first two  
rounds in which he finished at 1 under. 
</P>
<P>
	His analysis was succinct.  
</P>
<P>
	``I hit the ball poorly,'' he said. ``I put the ball in every  
poor spot you possibly could on every single hole.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	DIVOTS:@ First-round leaders Bob Estes and Brian Watts fell  
further back. Estes shot 80 to balloon to 6 over; Watts shot 78 to 
finish at 4 over. ... No. 18 played at a healthy average of .759 
strokes above par. There were only three birdies out of 79 rounds 
played. ... The highest winning score in the tournament is a 1-over 
par 289 by Mark Hayes and Jack Nicklaus, back in 1977 and 1978. 
That's when the tournament was played at Sawgrass Country Club. ... 
Scott Hoch finished in a tie for fourth place at 1-under 215. He is 
looking for his third consecutive top-5 finish at the Players. ... 
Duval hit first on the 11th hole, even though he had a bogey on No. 
10 and Ozaki had a par. ``It was a slip, that's all,'' Duval said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
