<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dad Sentenced in Kid's Heat Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BENTONVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- A man who left his daughter and another  
baby to die in his stifling car while he searched for arrowheads 
and mushrooms has been sentenced to 14 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Ricky Crisp, 24, could have been sentenced Friday to 40 years.  
He was convicted of second-degree murder in the deaths of his 
daughter, 16-month-old Vicky Crisp, and her cousin, 4-month-old 
Sidney Pippen. 
</P>
<P>
	The girls died of heat exhaustion and dehydration after the  
temperature in the black car reached at least 130 degrees last 
April. Prosecutors have said the pain was so severe that Vicky 
pulled out her hair. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Tom Keith followed the recommendation of jurors, who had  
been asked by Crisp's mother to be lenient. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ricky has already been punished,'' said Virginia Crisp. ``He's  
been punished for life. He says he doesn't like to go to town 
because he might see some babies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Brad Butler asked for the maximum. ``I encourage you  
to speak for these children,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Crisp's friend, Justin Griffith, 28, pleaded guilty this month  
to manslaughter and awaits sentencing. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffith said he and Crisp didn't plan to look for arrowheads  
and mushrooms for long, but lost track of time because they had 
taken drugs and alcohol. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
