<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Driver in Wis. Van Crash Charged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JANESVILLE, Wis. (AP) -- The driver of a speeding van that  
crashed and killed seven young people has been charged with 
vehicular homicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeremy Holmes, 20, was charged Friday with seven counts of  
negligent vehicular homicide and five counts of causing great 
bodily harm. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmes, of Clinton, Iowa, is accused of causing the van to roll  
over Thursday when he tried to switch places with a passenger after 
passing a police officer. Police said Holmes had so many tickets 
for speeding and other violations that he was not supposed to be 
driving in Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Six people were killed at the scene; a seventh died Friday at a  
hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The van, which police said was going at least 80 mph, was full  
of salespeople between the ages of 15 and 25 who were from as far 
away as Florida. They were heading to a Janesville motel where they 
had stayed for two weeks while they went on sales outings. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said the young people were selling magazines for an  
organization called Yes, which in ads promised ``Absolute Fun.'' 
The Capital Times of Madison, one of the newspapers that ran the 
ads, reported that the phone number on the classified ad bill was 
that of Subscriptions Plus Inc. of Bethany, Okla. 
</P>
<P>
	Labor officials in Wisconsin and Oklahoma, along with federal  
labor investigators, said they are looking into the work practices 
of Subscriptions Plus. 
</P>
<P>
	``The information we're getting from the employees' families and  
friends, well, `startling' is a good word,'' Oklahoma Labor 
Commissioner Brenda Reneau said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	She claims the company and its associates have illegally hired  
minors as independent contractors. Ms. Reneau said workers are paid 
in cash and aren't given tax forms, and that their wages are based 
on commissions from the subscriptions they sell. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it comes to pay day, they're not getting anything at all.  
All the food and lodging is being deducted from their pay. It 
appears, on the surface, to be in violation of the 
employee-employer relationship,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Subscriptions Plus President Karleen Hillery said her company  
has done nothing wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	``They get to eat, whether they sell or whether they don't,''  
she told The Daily Oklahoman of Oklahoma City. ``They're 
responsible for their own taxes, and they're given a 1099 form at 
the end of the year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yes officials have not responded to repeated messages left  
seeking comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
