<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 07:43:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Riley Drives Heat to Top of League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Pink panties. Metaphysical doctrine. Pat Riley even  
broke his toe once when he kicked a garbage can during one of his 
motivational speeches. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, even the most jaded Miami Heat players couldn't help but  
watch in disbelief as their coach soaked his head in a tub of icy 
water. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't see that every day, see a man put his head in a cold  
bucket of water which must have been 20 degrees,'' forward P.J. 
Brown said, chuckling. 
</P>
<P>
	Heat opponents often don't come up for air, either.  
</P>
<P>
	Despite a 1-3 start and the loss of starters Jamal Mashburn and  
Voshon Lenard to injuries, Miami has zoomed to the top of the NBA's 
Eastern Conference, tied with the Indiana Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Heat followed their opening stumble by winning 17 of their  
next 19, including 11 in a row at home. Opponents failed to reach 
90 points 11 straight times, an NBA record since the shot clock was 
introduced in the 1954-55 season. Miami and Utah are the only teams 
this season to hold every opponent under 50 percent shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unbelievable what (Riley) does down there,'' Indiana  
coach Larry Bird said. ``He gets his guys to play at a level no one 
else in the league can compete with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The secret, say the Heat, lies not in Riley's madness but his  
method. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the system here,'' said guard Tim Hardaway, who along  
with Alonzo Mourning, form Miami's cornerstones. ``We don't change 
nothing for nobody. Our offense and defense runs the same. When 
somebody gets hurt, it's your turn to step up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The system is built on a three-pronged foundation: relentless  
conditioning, stifling defense and a knowledge of opponents that 
would rival any NFL team's film study. 
</P>
<P>
	As with any Riley-coached team, it all starts with defense. Even  
when Riley was guiding the Los Angeles Lakers, Magic Johnson and 
James Worthy were quick to acknowledge many of those fast-break 
points came off steals or defensive stops. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not as pretty in Miami, but no less effective.  
</P>
<P>
	Defense is based on the ``help'' concept, making sure nobody has  
to defend a great player alone. Players must know exactly where to 
funnel opposing players, and know whem weakside help will be 
arriving. There are always two scouts on the road, and reports are 
extensive. 
</P>
<P>
	``Going into games, you know what your opponent's going to do,''  
said guard Terry Porter, a newcomer to Riley's system after 13 
seasons in Portland and Minnesota. ``He's very prepared for what's 
going to occur.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A prime example came March 17 at Atlanta. With Miami clinging to  
an 86-85 lead and 19 seconds left, Hardaway and Dan Majerle quickly 
recognized the Hawks' favorite pick-and-roll play with Mookie 
Blaylock and Steve Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	Majerle stepped up to jam the play. Hardaway fought through  
Smith's screen to stay in Blaylock's face. As time expired, 
Blaylock's awkward 19-foot jumper clanged off the rim. 
</P>
<P>
	Succeeding despite injuries is nothing new for Riley's Heat.  
Last season, Miami went 15-7 with Mourning out after knee surgery 
and 23-8 while Mashburn recovered from a broken thumb. One year 
earlier, Miami was 9-2 while Mourning recovered from a torn arch. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no reason to expect anybody not to do what they're  
capable of doing,'' said forward Keith Askins, a defensive 
specialist. ``We want guys to do the job they're supposed to do and 
things will take care of themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pieces fit together well. Porter, signed as a backup, is  
Miami's third-leading scorer and plays alongside Hardaway in crunch 
time. Clarence Weatherspoon, another free-agent pickup, ranks third 
on the team in rebounding. Askins clamps down on opposing big 
guards. Guard Rex Walters provides ball handling and timely 
shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	And there's Mourning and Hardaway, each averaging nearly 20  
points per game. Mourning is the NBA's top shot-blocker and has 15 
double-doubles. Hardaway leads the league in 3-pointers and ranks 
among the top 10 in assists. 
</P>
<P>
	Riley remains a master at inspiring the troops. But for all of  
his high-minded, new-age talk, he's not beyond using crude 
motivational ploys. He once threw a pair of pink panties among 
players in the locker room to suggest they weren't playing hard 
enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Not long after the Heat began turning things around, the team  
was in Detroit when Riley told the story of a youngster who asked 
his coach for advice on how to win. The coach dunked the kid's head 
in a pond, holding it under for several seconds. When the gasping 
youngster emerged, the coach said: ``You will win when winning is 
as important as that next breath.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miami beat the Pistons, sweeping a stretch of three games in  
three nights. Afterward, Riley came into the locker room and knelt 
beside a bucket of icy water used by players to soak their ankles. 
</P>
<P>
	Riley asked his players if they wanted to dunk his head  
underwater. Hearing no takers, he submerged his head and stayed 
there so long that players got concerned. He finally came up, 
looked at them and said, ``Until your last breath. Until your last 
breath.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown called the act ``an emotional booster.''  
</P>
<P>
	``I was shocked and bewildered a little, but also excited,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mashburn, recovering from a knee injury, will soon rejoin the  
Heat. Lenard's stress fracture in his leg should be healed by the 
playoffs. And more people now mention Miami as a favorite to become 
the first champion of the post-Michael Jordan era. 
</P>
<P>
	Riley wants to throw cold water on that talk.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're leading the Eastern Conference right now. The only thing  
we can do is surrender it,'' he said. ``How do you stay one step 
ahead of the posse and one step away from the street?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Count on Riley to go to extremes to figure it out.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
