<HEADLINE> Friend: Ark. Shooter Mad at Teacher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JONESBORO, Ark. (AP) -- One of the boys involved in last year's  
Jonesboro school shootings told an officer that the other shooter 
was mad at a teacher, according to an investigator's report. 
</P>
<P>
	The report by Craighead County Deputy Sheriff Terry McNatt was  
part of a case file on the shootings that was released last week by 
Deputy Prosecutor Mike Walden. Four students and a teacher died in 
the March 24 violence at Westside Middle School, and 10 other 
people were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	McNatt said in his report that he heard one of the arresting  
officers ask Mitchell Johnson, then 13, and Andrew Golden, then 11, 
why they fired the shots. 
</P>
<P>
	``The suspect (Mitchell) said, `Andrew was mad at a teacher,''  
the report said.	   Mitchell and Andrew were sentenced to held until age 18 at the 
state Division of Youth Services for the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no indication in McNatt's report of which teacher was  
the target of Andrew's anger. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew was in the class of sixth-grade teacher Shannon Wright,  
who died in the shooting. But the case file included ballistics 
reports indicating that the bullet that killed her was fired by 
Mitchell. 
</P>
</TEXT>
