<DOCNO> APW19990327.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 07:43:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wife of Hornets Owner Wants Divorce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE (AP) -- The wife of Charlotte Hornets owner George  
Shinn has filed for divorce in the wake of two women accusing her 
husband of sexual assaults. 
</P>
<P>
	Carolyn Shinn cites as grounds for the divorce that the couple  
have lived apart for more than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents filed in Mecklenburg County do not include terms  
of a possible financial settlement. The couple recently reached an 
agreement after months of negotiation, The Charlotte Observer 
reported today, quoting unnamed sources. 
</P>
<P>
	The Shinns recently have been dividing real estate holdings,  
titling property in Myrtle Beach, S.C., and two homes in Charlotte 
in Carolyn Shinn's name. George Shinn retained a house in Jupiter, 
Fla., and a waterfront home in Tega Cay, S.C. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tega Cay home was described as the scene where two women  
said they were sexually assaulted by Shinn in separate incidents 
before he and his wife separated. Shinn said the sex with both 
women was consensual. 
</P>
<P>
	The Shinns, who married in 1972, could not be reached Friday.  
Their attorneys declined comment. 
</P>
<P>
	A property settlement with Carolyn Shinn was not a major factor  
in George Shinn's recent efforts to sell a substantial interest in 
the Hornets, The Observer reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The franchise, which Shinn won for Charlotte in 1987, is valued  
at more than $100 million. 
</P>
<P>
	North Carolina's equitable-distribution law directs that nearly  
all assets accumulated during a marriage are considered marital 
property. The assets should be divided equally unless the parties 
agree to some other distribution, the law states. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple raised two sons and a daughter while George Shinn  
built a financial empire of real estate, business colleges and car 
dealerships. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Leslie Price, 29, of Matthews, accused Shinn of  
sexually assaulting her at his Tega Cay home. Prosecutors filed no 
criminal charges after an investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Price sued Shinn for damages. The civil trial could begin this  
spring. 
</P>
<P>
	This month, a former Hornets cheerleader alleged a similar  
sexual assault. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Tommy Pope said this week he is reconsidering his  
decision not to file charges in the Price case, in part because of 
the new allegation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
