<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Baywatch' To Film in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- G'day, ``Baywatch.''  
</P>
<P>
	The long-running syndicated television show is heading to  
Australia after a Teamsters official rejected a contract proposal 
to bring production to Hawaii from California, the show's creator 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Bonann said Teamsters Local 399 director Leo T. Reed would  
not agree to an 11 percent salary cut for Hawaii's movie and 
television industry drivers. That would have reduced minimum 
salaries from $1,840 a week to $1,641. 
</P>
<P>
	``They would not agree to any reduction in rates whatsoever, not  
one penny,'' an angry Bonann said from California. ``So the whole 
house of cards falls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Similar concessions were accepted by unions representing actors,  
directors and stage hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonann said Reed's decision cost Teamsters a potential $7  
million for six upcoming years of production on a new version of 
the show to be called ``Baywatch Hawaii.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Teamsters in Los Angeles have earned $10 million during the  
show's production there, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed did not return a telephone message left at his North  
Hollywood, Calif., office. 
</P>
<P>
	The show, which features David Hasselhoff and a crew of buff and  
busty lifeguards, is relocating from Los Angeles after nine years 
because of increasing costs and declining ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	It was headed to Queensland, Australia, until Hawaii made a  
pitch to bring the show to Honolulu and Haleiwa on Oahu's North 
Shore. 
</P>
<P>
	The state offered an incentive package including free airfare,  
hotel rooms and cars, other perks such as tax incentives and free 
location access, and $1.7 million to improve the Hawaii Film Studio 
and renovate the Haleiwa Recreation Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonann favored bringing the show here because it would have kept  
production in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The new show likely will be called ``Baywatch Down Under.''  
</P>
<P>
	``I wish it was `Aloha,' but it's `G'day,''' Bonann said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
