<HEADLINE> Public Defender Accused of Affair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The lawyer who unsuccessfully defended her client  
against first-degree murder charges has been removed from his case 
after she was accused of having sex with him. 
</P>
<P>
	Carmen L. Fischer, the public defender for Michael Sanders, was  
accused of having romantic interludes with him in jail, where he is 
awaiting sentencing in the so-called bounty slayings of a young 
couple. He could receive the death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Maricopa County Superior Court Judge Gregory Martin  
ruled the alleged affair, while not illegal, poses a conflict of 
interest that could hurt Sanders' case and ordered Fischer removed. 
</P>
<P>
	Detention officers testified they saw Fischer and Sanders  
kissing, embracing and touching in prison visitation rooms and said 
they had engaged in sex. During a hearing on the issue Fischer and 
her representatives ultimately refused to say whether that was 
true, acknowledging only a ``personal relationship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders accused of being among five men who broke into the home  
of Chris Foote and Spring Wright in the middle of the night and 
shot them to death in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	They claimed to be bounty hunters looking for a bail jumper, but  
prosecutors said that was a ruse for robbery. Sanders was convicted 
last year of two counts of first-degree murder. 
</P>
<P>
	The Arizona State Bar announced Friday it would conduct its own  
investigation of Fischer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
