<DOCNO> APW19990327.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 06:03:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Muslim Pilgrims Continue Hajj Acts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINA, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Some 2 million Muslim pilgrims  
performed the symbolic ritual of stoning the devil before dawn here 
today, throwing pebbles at a massive pillar. 
</P>
<P>
	They then headed back to Mecca -- some by foot, some by bus -- to  
walk seven times around the Kaaba, the black-draped cube in the 
center of the Grand Mosque. The two rituals are considered the peak 
of the three-day pilgrimage, or hajj, which began Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have stoned the devil. I have circled the Kaaba. Thank God,  
I am a pilgrim now,'' said Mohammed Osman from Sudan. He spoke 
after catching his breath from the strain of circling the Kaaba 
among 200,000 other worshipers. 
</P>
<P>
	In Mecca, pilgrims also slaughtered rams and oxen in a ceremony  
performed across the Islamic world today as Muslims marked one of 
their most important holidays, Eid al-Adha, the Feast of Sacrifice. 
</P>
<P>
	The white-robed pilgrims took at least two hours to cover the  
six-mile journey from Mina to Mecca today. With the massive crowds, 
traffic inched along the road. People sat on the roofs of buses and 
clung to the back windows, their feet dangling in the air. 
</P>
<P>
	Others seemed to enjoy the pre-dawn walk back to Mecca under the  
stars. It was cool in comparison to Friday's daytime temperatures 
of 104 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilgrims' day began with a ritual symbolizing the rejection  
of Satan's temptations. They threw seven pebbles at a 50-foot 
obelisk of light gray stone that represents the devil. With each 
pebble, the pilgrims chanted ``Allahu Akbar,'' or ``God is Great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sacrifices of livestock opens the three-day Eid al-Adha  
holiday, which commemorates the sacrifice by the biblical Abraham, 
or Ibrahim, of a ram in place of his son. 
</P>
<P>
	Celebrations took place around the Muslim world.  
</P>
<P>
	In Beirut, Lebanese Muslims filled mosques for dawn prayers and  
heard sermons praising government reforms and calling for further 
efforts to weed out corruption. In the southern suburbs, a 
predominantly Shiite Muslim area, children flocked to amusement 
parks. 
</P>
<P>
	In Cairo, the streets were empty of traffic. Young Egyptians  
packed the decks of riverboats for cruises up the Nile. Men 
slaughtered sheep and cattle in backyards and alleys while women 
cooked lavish lunches in keeping with the Eid's emphasis on family 
gatherings. 
</P>
<P>
	In Amman, the death of King Hussein in February cast a pall over  
the holiday. Mosques delivered special prayers for Hussein, who had 
ruled for more than 46 years. King Abdullah went to mosque and then 
visited the grave of his father for more prayers. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first time that the Jordanian family celebrates a  
holiday without its leader, the father of all Jordanians,'' Rakan 
Majali wrote in an editorial in Ad-Dustour newspaper, the nation's 
second-largest daily. 
</P>
<P>
	The Saudis have deployed more than 45,000 people to help  
organize this year's 2.3 million pilgrims. 
</P>
<P>
	All able-bodied Muslims are required to perform the hajj at  
least once in their lives if they can afford it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
