<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Morgan Freeman's Tale of Mutiny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- On July 17, 1944, a ship loaded with  
munitions exploded at Port Chicago in San Francisco Bay, killing 
320 men, most of them black sailors. It was the worst home-front 
disaster of World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	The tragedy and its legal aftermath are the subject of  
``Mutiny,'' an NBC movie airing on Sunday, March 28, at 9 p.m 
(EST). 
</P>
<P>
	Before the explosion, the sailors had complained about long  
hours and unsafe conditions for handling the munitions -- a task for 
which they were untrained. Afterward, they were assigned the same 
duty at another Navy base. Fearing the same fate that befell their 
comrades, 50 sailors refused their assignments. 
</P>
<P>
	They were court-martialed and sentenced to 15 years at hard  
labor for mutiny. After the war, President Truman pardoned them. 
The survivors of Port Chicago still hope for an act of Congress to 
exonerate them with honorable discharges. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Jai White, Duane Martin and David Ramsey portray the  
sailor-stevedores. Morgan Freeman does not appear, but served as 
executive producer through his film and television company, 
Revelations Entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	A three-time Oscar nominee for acting, in ``Street Smart,''  
``Driving Miss Daisy'' and ``The Shawshank Redemption,'' Freeman 
started the company two years ago. ``The idea was to make a 
specific kind of movie, hopefully ones that would inform us as well 
as entertain us,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman noted a similar footnote-to-history background for two  
honored black-heritage films in which he appeared in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I think of things like 'Glory' and 'Amistad,' these are  
moments in American history that were completely hidden away. There 
are history buffs who know something about the stories, but the 
general public knows nothing. I thoroughly believe in the dictum 
about knowing your history in order to know yourself. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a country, we don't know ourselves. We just know what we've  
been told in the general history books.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman admits he had been unaware of the Port Chicago disaster.  
</P>
<P>
	``I knew there had been a massive explosion during World War  
II,'' he said. ``I didn't know that Port Chicago is in California. 
This whole experience has been a history lesson.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nor did he know about the mutiny and the support the sailors got  
from Thurgood Marshall, then of the NAACP and later Supreme Court 
justice. Marshall is portrayed by Joe Morton. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mutiny'' portrays a wartime Navy as segregated as the Deep  
South of that era. Morgan Freeman knows that scene. 
</P>
<P>
	``I grew up in Mississippi in a segregated society,'' he  
remarked. ``To me, that was all to my good. I am who I am because 
of who I was. I didn't grow up in a society that told me one thing 
and showed me another. You need a face on it to deal with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For ``Mutiny,'' Freeman visited filming locations and took part  
in preproduction, including the bane of most actors -- auditions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's such a hard process,'' said Freeman, who went through  
plenty of them in his early career.'' 'Just read this paragraph for 
me.' You almost make an arbitrary decision: Is this actor nervous? 
Can he do the job?'' 
</P>
<P>
	He recalled one of his worst experiences on the other side of  
the table, auditioning for Sidney Poitier, who was directing a 
play, ``Welcome to Morningside Heights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I was working with another young actor who hyperventilated. He  
started to shake, and I had to walk him backstage so he wouldn't 
pass out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't get the job anyway, because Sidney was going to give  
it to Lou Gossett, who was a friend of his from 'Raisin in the 
Sun'.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990327.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 02:21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Maintains Military Style </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As he guides the U.S. role in the NATO  
airstrikes on Yugoslavia, President Clinton is not hunched in a war 
room surrounded by maps and stern generals in uniform. 
</P>
<P>
	His preferred setting is the Oval Office, with foreign policy  
advisers in business suits -- and at least one in uniform -- settled 
back on yellow sofas. 
</P>
<P>
	With no military experience, Clinton avoids the image of the  
saber-rattling commander-in-chief. 
</P>
<P>
	``The style seems to be to bring the two sides together, then  
carry a big stick,'' said John Mueller, a University of Rochester 
political scientist who has written about presidents and war. ``The 
hope is that the threat would be enough. That works fine if they 
capitulate. If they don't, you're left with the dilemma of using 
the stick or looking foolish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the assault two days old, the president had a videotaped  
message beamed into Yugoslavia by satellite and sent on the 
Internet Friday. That tactic -- friendly words for a nation's people 
while military action is focused against its leader -- is one 
Clinton has used before, with Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also had Secretary of State Madeleine Albright -- whose  
father was a Czech diplomat in Belgrade before World War II -- 
deliver a message in the Serbs' own language. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hello. I am glad to have this opportunity to speak directly to  
the people of Serbia at this critical time,'' she said. ``As you 
can see, I remember a little Serbian, albeit with a Czech accent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is the first president in a half-century who has no  
military background. He seemed uncomfortable about that during his 
first term, even going to the length of taking lessons in saluting 
from former national security adviser Tony Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of his lack of experience and because he is the first  
of the post-World War II, Vietnam-generation presidents, he has 
tended to be more deferential to military points of view than 
others,'' said Ivon Daalder, who served as the National Security 
Council's director of European affairs during Clinton's first term. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has not been willing to take on the military, even if it  
was evident that doing so may have served his purposes, foreign 
policy and otherwise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But when delivering a sensitive foreign policy message, such as  
his address to the nation from the Oval Office earlier this week, 
Clinton doesn't simply recite the lines his security experts hand 
him. He constantly reworks the texts. 
</P>
<P>
	During his first term, Clinton oversaw U.S. intervention in  
Somalia, where 18 soldiers died, followed by the humiliating 
withdrawal of American forces. He sent troops to Haiti in a 
successful mission to reinstate elected President Jean-Bertrand 
Aristide, then passed off command to a multinational peacekeeping 
force. 
</P>
<P>
	And in 1995, there were the airstrikes over Bosnia, with no  
American fatalities. 
</P>
<P>
	Well into his second term, Clinton is more at ease. Last fall,  
he ordered airstrikes on Afghanistan and Sudan in retaliation for 
bombings at U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania. There have been 
several flare-ups with Iraq, and earlier this year nearly daily 
bombings of Iraqi sites. 
</P>
<P>
	As commander-in-chief, Clinton is ``detail oriented,'' said  
David Leavy, spokesman for the National Security Council. ``He asks 
a lot of questions and demands a lot of answers. He has made clear 
that he wants to be briefed on any and all important developments. 
He wants to think two or three moves down the chessboard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In times like these, aides say, Clinton is a hands-on manager --  
but not so hands-on that he feels he should select bombing targets 
as President Johnson sometimes did during the Vietnam War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
