<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress To Debate Dairy Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Depending on your point of view, letting  
groups of states join together to set milk prices in their region 
either helps stabilize the cost of that gallon jug against market 
swings or artificially inflates the price, at consumer's expense. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon, Congress will decide the future of such regional dairy  
compacts as lawmakers tackle how to regulate one sector of an 
agricultural economy reeling from depressed prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress agreed to compacts as part of the farm reform law in  
1996. Only one now operates, the Northeast Dairy Compact, which 
began in 1997 and includes Connecticut, Maine, Massachusetts, New 
Hampshire, Rhode Island and Vermont. 
</P>
<P>
	But other states want to join that compact or form their own.  
</P>
<P>
	The compacts allow states to band together and set what they  
consider a ``fair price'' for fluid milk. A commission funded with 
dairy producer contributions controls the operations and 
establishes a price higher than the federal government's for the 
commodity. 
</P>
<P>
	The Northeast compact is set to expire Oct. 1 unless Congress  
agrees to reauthorize it. Meantime, a dozen southern states, 
including Georgia, Mississippi and Louisiana, are pushing for 
congressional approval to start a Southern Dairy Compact. 
</P>
<P>
	But some lawmakers, particularly those from the Upper Midwest,  
complain that the Northeast compact frustrates farmers from their 
states who might want to sell milk in New England. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, Wisconsin lawmakers blocked a provision in last fall's  
budget discussions that would have extended the life of the 
Northeast compact. 
</P>
<P>
	Compact proponents say the regional agreements protect consumers  
from fluctuating prices. They note that the average retail price of 
a gallon of whole milk in Boston from April to June 1998 was $2.69, 
compared with a range of $2.76 in Philadelphia to $3.12 in Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	``This program does not cost the government anything at all,''  
said Robert Gray, executive director of the States Ratification 
Committee, a coalition of leaders from state agriculture 
departments of agriculture who are pushing the compact idea. 
</P>
<P>
	``The compact has really worked as a safety net to see that when  
you have these deep valleys, there is some sort of cushion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just this month, the government said the price producers receive  
for milk would fall $6 to $10.27 per hundred pounds of milk, the 
sharpest decline from one month to another in the industry's 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those of us who belong to the existing Northeast Dairy Compact  
are able to soften the blow to our farmers,'' said Leon Graves, 
commissioner of Vermont's Department of Food and Markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Odom, Louisiana's Agriculture and Forestry Commissioner and  
a leading backer of a Southern Dairy Compact, said compacts are 
``sound public policy'' offering stable prices for both consumers 
and farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	Odom and others argue that since the 1996 farm law reduced  
government intervention in the dairy industry, compacts help 
maintain the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents, from milk processors to consumer activists, tell a  
different story. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our interest is to sell milk. Compacts interfere with that.  
Higher costs decrease consumption,'' said E. Linwood Tipton, 
president of the International Dairy Foods Association, which 
represents processors. 
</P>
<P>
	Added John Schnittker, an economist with Public Voice for Food  
and Health Policy: Compacts are ``effectively cheating consumers of 
savings on fluid milk products.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Complicating the debate over compacts' future is the issue of  
reforming the federal milk marketing order, which basically is the 
federal government's pricing system. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the order program, different parts of the country are  
divided into ``marketing orders'' which are arranged by the 
agriculture secretary and which set the minimum price of milk in 
those areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress in 1996 told USDA to consolidate the 31 existing orders  
to between 10 and 14. The agency has proposed 11 and Agriculture 
Secretary Dan Glickman this week is expected to release the final 
plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the price paid to compact producers exceeds that of the  
marketing order, some groups such as Public Voice complain it 
eventually filters down to consumers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
