<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New York Street Crime Unit Revamped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The police department announced major changes in  
its elite crimefighting unit on the heels of reports that four of 
its white members were indicted for murder in the killing of an 
unarmed black immigrant. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers in the Street Crime Unit will now wear uniforms instead  
of plainclothes, and 50 slots at the predominately white division 
will be reassigned to minority police officers, under changes 
announced Friday by Police Commissioner Howard Safir. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes are partly in response to concerns voiced by  
political and community leaders as well as city residents, Safir 
said. The changes may take place as early as Sunday, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Safir, Mayor Giuliani and the unit have been under intense  
criticism and scrutiny ever since four of the unit's officers fired 
41 bullets at Amadou Diallo on Feb. 4 in the vestibule of his Bronx 
home. He was hit 19 times. 
</P>
<P>
	A source close to the case told The Associated Press on Thursday  
that a grand jury had decided to indict all four officers for 
second-degree murder. The indictment remains sealed. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers have yet to say publicly what happened, but a  
lawyer representing one of them has said they believed the 
22-year-old street vendor from Guinea was reaching for a gun. 
Critics have said Diallo -- who was black -- may have been acting 
strangely because he was approached at night by the four white 
officers in plainclothes. 
</P>
<P>
	Safir said clothing has apparently caused confusion in some  
neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was explained to me a number of times that an individual  
would be followed by a nondescript car, three people in 
plainclothes would get out of the car, and a couple of people said 
to me: 'I just kept going because I didn't know who they were,''' 
Safir said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Diallo's killing, federal and state officials launched  
probes into the department, and more than 1,000 people have been 
arrested in civil disobedience demonstrations outside police 
headquarters in the past two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Jesse Jackson was among 216 people arrested Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	Safir said he plans to promote about 300 of the 380 Street Crime  
members to the rank of detective specialist, reassign 50 of them to 
robbery and apprehension units and earmark their Street Crime slots 
for minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	He said since Diallo's death, there has been a drop in 67  
percent arrests made by the Street Crime Unit. Safir blamed the 
media for the decrease, saying its members have been ``relentless 
in vilifying the Street Crime Unit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The unit, whose motto is ``We Own the Night,'' was formed in  
1971, and expanded in 1997 by Giuliani. Because the unit works in 
high-violence areas, its officers have always worn plainclothes to 
fit into the neighborhoods they patrol. 
</P>
<P>
	The unit commander, Inspector Bruce Smolka Jr., said he'll take  
a ``wait and see'' attitude about the potential impact of putting 
his employees in uniform. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani lent his support to the plan.  
</P>
<P>
	``I am certain these changes will result in positive  
improvements,'' he said in a statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
