<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pedro Martinez Ready for Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- Pedro Martinez has only one spring  
training start left. He doesn't really need it. 
</P>
<P>
	Not after striking out 10 and allowing three hits in six innings  
Friday against Texas. Not after giving up only two runs in 20 
innings over his last four starts. Not after reducing his 
exhibition ERA to 1.29 and improving his record to 3-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez, 19-7 with a 2.89 ERA with Boston last year after  
winning the NL Cy Young Award with Montreal in 1997, is ready for 
opening day. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I am the same way I was (Friday), I'm ready to go,''  
Martinez said. 
</P>
<P>
	He left the game with a 4-1 lead and the Red Sox went on to a  
10-3 win over the Rangers. Martinez started by striking out leadoff 
hitter Tom Goodwin. Then he picked up the pace. 
</P>
<P>
	He struck out the side in the second, fanned one batter in the  
third, two in the fourth, two in the fifth and another in the 
sixth. He struck out eight of the nine starters, allowed only five 
balls out of the infield and walked two. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had good command of his pitches, a lot of strike-one  
counts,'' Boston manager Jimy Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez left his previous start after six shutout innings  
against Pittsburgh but had no strikeouts. The difference Friday? 
</P>
<P>
	``An extra day off, probably, and also the fastball was going  
way up (in the strike zone),'' Martinez said. ``That was the 
reason, extra juice and the extra rest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now he's on schedule to pitch the opener April 5 at Kansas City.  
His final exhibition start is set for Wednesday against Pittsburgh, 
which has scored only once in 10 innings against him this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez has had only one poor performance. It came in his first  
exhibition game March 6 when he lasted one inning against 
Cincinnati and allowed four runs, three walks and one hit, although 
only one run was earned. 
</P>
<P>
	Four days later, he pitched four shutout innings against the  
world champion New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel good,'' Martinez said. ``I'm already past the fifth  
inning. That's a quality outing. I think that will be good enough 
the first few outings and, from there on, stretch it out a 
little.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez wouldn't mind matching his opening-day performance last  
season. In his first game with the Red Sox, he struck out 11, and 
allowed only three hits and two walks in seven innings in a 2-0 win 
at Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	By the All-Star break, he was 11-2. Now he seems in midseason  
form nine days before the season begins. But he still has some 
things he'd like to work on. 
</P>
<P>
	``From now on, it's just a matter of keeping my focus and  
keeping my mind in the game and staying healthy,'' Martinez said. 
``If I manage to do that, the rest is going to happen by itself.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
