<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doug Gilmour Sidelined for Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Doug Gilmour, whose signing as a  
free agent failed to turn the Chicago Blackhawks into a playoff 
contender, will be sidelined the rest of the season with a bulging 
disk in his back. 
</P>
<P>
	The 35-year-old center is considering microsurgery to shave the  
disk that is pressing on his sciatic nerve. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's starting to go down my leg a lot more,'' Gilmour said of  
the pain. ``I was trying to play for Lorne (coach Lorne Molleken) 
and I wanted to see if I could get through the whole year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gilmour, who signed a three-year, $18 million contract in the  
offseason, spoke with Blackhawks general manager Bob Murray after a 
tie with Boston on Thursday and they decided that Gilmour should 
stop playing. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilmour intends to get a second opinion in California before  
making a final decision on his back. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not major,'' said Gilmour, whose 16 goals and 40 assists  
was second on the Blackhawks in scoring. ``It's not career-ending 
or anything like that. It's something that I have to attend to. 
Maybe in three weeks it will go away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gilmour had played in the Blackhawks' first 72 games, the last  
coming on Thursday night in a 3-3 tie with Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Molleken felt Gilmour should have gotten help sooner.  
</P>
<P>
	``He shouldn't have been playing for the last six weeks or so,''  
said the interim coach who replaced Dirk Graham 14 games ago. 
``He's been playing in a lot of pain. We know what Dougie Gilmour 
is all about. He competes on the ice in all the tough areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been many times we told him to take the equipment  
off, but there was no way,'' Molleken said. ``We just about had to 
rassle him down to the ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gilmour joined the NHL in 1983-84 and he has played in 1,197  
games, scoring 397 goals and 835 assists. A winner of the Selke 
Trophy as the NHL's best defensive forward in 1993, he ranks 20th 
on the NHL's career assists list. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilmour has played with St. Louis, Calgary, Toronto, New Jersey  
and now Chicago. He won a Stanley Cup in 1989 with the Flames in 
Calgary and won a gold medal as a member of Team Canada in the 1987 
Canada Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilmour was acquired by New Jersey on Feb. 27, 1997 from Toronto  
in a five player deal. While the Devils wanted him to stay after 
last season, the veteran could not turn down the money offered by 
the Blackhawks, who are on the verge of missing the playoffs for 
second straight year after making them the previous 28 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
