<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990327.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 06:03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 35 Dead Remain in French Tunnel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COURMAYEUR, Italy (AP) -- The charred bodies of at least 35  
victims remained in the Mont Blanc tunnel while officials tried to 
figure out why a fire aboard a truck carrying flour and margarine 
turned so deadly. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't until late Friday afternoon, two days after the blaze  
broke out, that firefighters from three countries were finally able 
to extinguish it. 
</P>
<P>
	The 7-mile tunnel under Western Europe's highest peak is a key  
route between France and Italy, handling some 4,000 vehicles daily. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Italian side, tunnel authority director Francesco Colombo  
put the death toll at 35. On the French side, Philippe Pathous, 
fire chief for the Haute-Savoie region, said as many as 40 people 
might have been killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said today it could be another two days before the  
tunnel is safe enough for a complete inspection and for a final 
death toll to be determined. 
</P>
<P>
	The bodies, most found in and around their cars, were still in  
the tunnel, left in place so investigators could conduct their 
inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	Rene Guichard, an investigator for the French state prosecutor  
in the Haute-Savoie region, said today that officials could start 
removing bodies on the French side of the tunnel later in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, French Interior Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement  
arrived in Chamonix today to take part in a funeral service for 
George Tosello, a 54-year-old French firefighter who died of a 
heart attack after being evacuated from the tunnel Wednesday. 
Firefighters on the Italian side of the tunnel observed a moment of 
silence in memory of Tosello. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire raised questions about the emergency systems in the  
tunnel, which is equipped with ventilation equipment and 17 
shelters, each of which can hold dozens of people. The shelters are 
designed to resist heat and poisonous fumes for two hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a handful of the victims managed to reach the shelters.  
</P>
<P>
	Many felt security measures were not enough. ``For a long time  
now it has been said that the Mont Blanc tunnel is no longer 
adapted'' to heavy truck traffic, said the mayor of Chamonix, 
Michel Charlet. He called for a ban on heavy trucks in the tunnel. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombo said an alert was sounded 60 seconds after the fire  
broke out, and he insisted that tunnel officials from both 
countries responded promptly to the disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the survivors was the driver of the Belgian truck that  
caught fire Wednesday morning, causing the disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilbert Degraves, driving from France to Italy, said he was  
alerted to the fire when oncoming vehicles flashed their 
headlights, about four miles into the tunnel. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoke billowed from his truck. He stopped, checked underneath  
and ``it exploded,'' Degraves, a truck driver for 25 years, told 
French RTL radio. ``It was a ball of fire for about 30 seconds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the victims was Pierlucio Tinazzi, a 33-year-old Italian  
tunnel employee. He saved 10 people, making repeated trips into the 
tunnel on his motorcycle before succumbing to the fire, Colombo 
told a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``I consider him a real hero,'' Colombo said. ``He did his duty,  
and we are very grateful to him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An Italian family of four from a nearby village was also killed,  
as were five other Italians, a French firefighter, and a French 
couple from Lyon. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first fatal fire in the tunnel, which was the longest  
in the world when President Charles de Gaulle opened it in 1965. 
</P>
<P>
	The tunnel operator in France, Mont Blanc Tunnel and Highway,  
said about 20 tractor-trailer trucks and 11 cars were destroyed in 
the blaze. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures in the tunnel at one point reached at least 1,832  
degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	About 100 firefighters from France, Italy and Switzerland  
battled poisonous fumes and searing temperatures for two days to 
tame the blaze. For the first time, they managed to penetrate the 
length of the tunnel on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Using a spray mist, they cooled it down to 158 degrees, then to  
122 degrees. Smoke rose from their protective gear as they emerged 
from the tunnel. They declined to speak to reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Poisonous fumes blowing through the passage forced rescuers to  
focus on the Italian side. The stench of burning rubber hung in the 
mountain air. 
</P>
<P>
	The burning flour aboard the Belgian truck immediately thickened  
the smoke in the tunnel, Colombo said. 
</P>
<P>
	French Transport Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot said the tunnel  
would remain closed for several weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
