<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's ruling party could lose the 2000  
presidential race -- in what would be its first defeat at the polls 
in 70 years -- if internal divisions develop, said former President 
Miguel de la Madrid, according to local reports Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	De la Madrid's comments came after a maverick candidate for the  
party's top leadership post quit the race, claiming the group's 
decisions were not democratic. 
</P>
<P>
	``Evidently, there is a risk of losing the presidency in 2000 if  
a serious fracture in the party occurs,'' de la Madrid said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	De la Madrid -- a member of the ruling Institutional  
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, who served as president from 1982-88 -- 
said Rodolfo Echeverria's decision Thursday to quit the race ``may 
weaken the party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say the other candidate in the race, Jose Gonzalez  
Fernandez, was handpicked by President Ernesto Zedillo, and is 
guaranteed the post. 
</P>
<P>
	The party will vote for the presidency Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Robbers shot a South American  
swimming champion in Rio de Janeiro when she evaded their attempt 
to steal her car, hospital staff said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mariana Moraes Rangel, 23, the continent's 800 meter freestyle  
champion, was wounded in the thigh late Friday, said Catia 
Oliveira, a spokeswoman for the Souza Aguira hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite her wound, the Brazilian swimmer drove on to a gas  
station to get help, said Oliveira. She had surgery in hospital and 
was expected to recover fully. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Troops rescued a German man and four  
Colombians abducted early Saturday by suspected leftist rebels on a 
southern backroad, the army reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The guerrillas briefly exchanged gunfire with soldiers, and two  
of at least four fleeing rebels were detained, the local army 
commander, Gen. Carlos Ospina, told The Associated Press. No 
injuries were reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The German was identified as Joseph Meir, 58. It was not  
possible to confirm his identify through the German Embassy in 
Bogota. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colombian hostages included an engineer, a landowner and a  
79-year-old man, the army said. The identity of the fourth 
Colombian was not known. 
</P>
<P>
	The five were abducted in El Castillo, a rural town 75 miles  
southeast of Bogota in Meta State. 
</P>
<P>
	Ospina blamed the kidnapping on Colombia's largest guerrilla  
group, the leftist Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no comment from the rebel group, which is active in  
the region and frequently kidnaps foreigners and Colombians for 
ransom. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Airport police seized more than half a  
ton of cocaine hidden in steel drums and destined for Guatemala, 
authorities said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Twelve containers carrying 1,300 pounds of cocaine were  
discovered in a routine search late-Friday of a warehouse at 
Bogota's El Dorado international airport, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The drugs were sealed in more than 600 plastic packages stashed  
inside the drums, which also contained chemicals. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said they detained two men Friday in connection with the  
shipment, which was registered to a Colombian company. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombia is the world's largest source of cocaine, exporting  
more than 80 percent of the cocaine sold in the United States. 
</P>
