<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Langdon Let Game Find Him </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- He did what the good ones always do  
when things go bad. Trajan Langdon let the game find him. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first two-thirds of Saturday night's semifinal, Duke's  
best player was more a rumor than a fact. He passed up his own 
shots and defended like a devil in blue instead. He crashed the 
boards and chased loose balls into the seats. He threw passes that 
split the seams in the Michigan State zone like a man freed from a 
yearlong diet. 
</P>
<P>
	But in that split-second when the game was there for the taking,  
Langdon never hesitated. He stepped forward and grabbed it by the 
throat. 
</P>
<P>
	With eight minutes left and the Spartans surging to within  
51-48, Langdon caught the ball on the right side behind the 3-point 
arc and let fly a jump shot. It was the same one that he'd taken a 
thousand times on frozen playgrounds in Alaska, except then he was 
still a schoolboy, stuck wearing gloves and a coat. 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't matter. The result was the same.  
</P>
<P>
	``That,'' Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski said once he had the chance  
to catch his breath, ``was the biggest shot of the game.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
