<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cheap Steel Imports Hurt Small Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HICKMAN, Ark. (AP) -- Rick Sweetman recalls what happened when  
his employer, Nucor Corp., cut production last year because of 
competition from cheap imported steel. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it wasn't for deer meat, my little girl and I wouldn't have  
eaten,'' Sweetman said. ``I took up hunting and fishing with a real 
zeal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sweetman, 37, has worked at the Nucor-Hickman plant since it  
opened for business in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	His seven years on the Nucor production line accustomed him to a  
healthy paycheck, especially for northeastern Arkansas. Annual 
salaries averaged between $50,000 and $55,000 until last summer, 
according to plant manager Dave Chase. 
</P>
<P>
	But production at the plant, which turns out rolls of sheet  
steel, has been cut, largely because of cheap steel imports. 
Imports surged last year in the wake of the Asian economic crisis 
that lowered demand for steel abroad and forced foreign producers 
to turn to U.S. outlets. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first quarter last year was the best production rate  
ever,'' Chase recalled, with Nucor-Hickman producing 540,000 tons. 
By the final three months of 1998, Chase said, production was down 
by two-thirts to only 180,000 tons. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're selling stuff at $230 a ton that we're selling for  
$400 a ton,'' said Dan DiMicco, manager at a sister plant, 
Nucor-Yamato in nearby Armorel. 
</P>
<P>
	This corner of northeastern Arkansas produces more steel than  
all but one other county in the nation, Lake County, home of Gary, 
Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	Across the country, steel producers blame at least 10,000  
layoffs and three bankruptcies on imports. 
</P>
<P>
	So was welcome news that the U.S. Commerce Department reported  
this past week that steel imports into the United States during 
February actually dropped below pre-1998 levels. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall imports were at 2 million metric tons, 15 percent below  
the 1997 monthly average of 2.4 million, preliminary statistics 
released by the Commerce Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, it also said that two targets of recent U.S. government  
sanctions against ``dumping'' of cheap steal -- Russia and Brazil -- 
posted slight increases in shipments. That could give ammunition to 
Congressional representatives seeking stiffer penalties from the 
Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	While slumping sales and falling production have yet to prompt  
any layoffs at the two Nucor plants in Mississippi County, Ark., 
they have cut the generous production bonuses workers counted on in 
the past. When production was high, an average of two-thirds of 
each worker's pay had been comprised of bonuses. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, paychecks are closer to basic pay rates, which range from  
$17,600 a year to $24,000, says Phil Baker, 25, who, like Sweetman, 
works on the steel production line. Baker says his income dropped 
$12,000 from roughly $80,000 he had made in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker says his four children quickly found out that times were  
lean. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was, `Daddy, can we have this?' -- `No, we can't afford  
it,''' he recalled in a recent interview along with Sweetman and 
three other Nucor workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't seen a movie in a year,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The five said they knew of no one who had to give up a house.  
``But a lot of new vehicles went back,'' said Chad Utermark, 30, a 
supervisor at Nucor. 
</P>
<P>
	While Nucor officials say the lean times will continue until the  
government eliminates import dumping, they also express confidence 
Charlotte, N.C.-based company will survive, mainly because Nucor's 
plants are heavily automated and labor efficient. 
</P>
<P>
	However, for the towns affected, the import crisis goes beyond  
just the steel plants. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies that supply products and services to the Nucor plants  
in Mississippi County have been hard hit by job cuts. The county's 
unemployment rate in December was nearly 13 percent, up from almost 
10 percent last April. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ripple effect for us is just unbelievable,'' said Harold  
Wright, a local chamber of commerce chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to diversify, the chamber is now looking to attract  
plastics factories 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	TICKER   	
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Corp. offered to settle its federal antitrust case,  
but received a cool reception from the government. Settlement 
negotiations will begin in earnest early next week ... Comcast 
Corp. is buying MediaOne Group Inc. for $44.3 billion, uniting the 
nation's third- and fourth-largest cable operators in the 
industry's richest merger ever ... OPEC nations voted to cut crude 
oil production deeply and maintain the reductions for a year, 
trying to revive long-slumping oil prices ... Following its 
acquisition of Netscape Communications Corp., America Online Inc. 
plans to cut 1,000 of the combined company's 12,000 employees ... 
American manufacturers last month suffered the sharpest drop in 
more than seven years in new orders for airplanes, electronics and 
other big-ticket goods. 

</P>
</TEXT>
