<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. To Document Serb Atrocities  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today Serb troops  
continue to attack ethnic Albanian civilians in Kosovo even as 
NATO's bombs systematically target the forces of Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic. Clinton reaffirmed his determination to 
``defuse a powder keg at the heart of Europe. Our military 
operation has been under way for several nights now. In this time, 
Serb troops have continued attacks on unarmed men, women and 
children,'' Clinton said in his weekly radio address. ``This is all 
the more reason for us to stay the course.'' Clinton said he was 
``deeply impressed by the solidarity'' of the 19 NATO countries and 
thanked U.S. military personnel for ``risking their lives to 
protect peace in the Balkans.'' 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Strikes Move Nearer Belgrade  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- More reports of heavy fighting and  
Serb atrocities in Kosovo emerged today after NATO carried its 
offensive in Yugoslavia closer to Belgrade in the heaviest of three 
nights of attacks. State-run media showed pictures of explosions 
and fires in Belgrade suburbs caused by ``NATO criminals'' and 
claimed civilians were killed and injured. British Defense 
Secretary George Robertson told a daily news briefing today that 
atrocities by Milosevic's forces in Kosovo continued. ``The Serbs 
are bombarding villages to the point of obliteration,'' Robertson 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	Myanmar Activist's Husband Dies  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Michael Aris, the husband of Myanmar  
opposition leader and Nobel laureate Aung San Suu Kyi, died today 
in a London hospital at age 53. Myanmar's military government had 
denied Aris, who was ill with prostate cancer, a visa to enter 
Myanmar and see his wife one last time before he died. Western 
governments had urged the Myanmar government to grant Aris a visa 
on humanitarian grounds, but the military government refused and 
instead urged Suu Kyi to visit her husband in Britain. 

</P>
<P>
	Dr. Kevorkian Convicted of Murder  
</P>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- Dr. Jack Kevorkian was convicted of  
second-degree murder for giving an ailing man a lethal injection 
and putting it all on videotape. Kevorkian, 70, could get a life 
term at his April 14 sentencing for the death of 52-year-old Thomas 
Youk, who suffered from Lou Gehrig's disease. ``Manslaughter, I 
could understand how they would arrive at that. But murder? This?'' 
Kevorkian said. ``They must have been an astonishingly cruel 
jury.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Pastor Suspended Over Gay Vows  
</P>
<P>
	DOWNERS GROVE, Ill. (AP) -- A Methodist minister who officiated  
at the ``marriage'' of two gay men has been suspended for 
disobeying church law. It was the first test of the denomination's 
ban on same-sex ceremonies. The suspension begins July 5 and 
continues until the Rev. Gregory Dell signs a statement saying he 
will comply with church law or until the law is changed. Earlier in 
the day, a jury of pastors decided 10-3 that Dell disobeyed church 
law when he presided over the ``holy union'' of two Chicago men in 
September. 

</P>
<P>
	Nissan, Renault Agreement Signed  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Renault and Nissan agreed today that the French  
automaker would pump $5.4 billion into Nissan's debt-laden 
operations in a deal creating the world's fourth-largest auto 
partnership. Under the deal, Renault becomes the largest 
shareholder in Nissan. Together, the two will have an output of 4.8 
million vehicles and the ability to develop ``strong synergies'' 
worth $3.3 billion for the 2000-2002 period, the companies said. 

</P>
<P>
	Lewinsky Russian Book Tour Canceled  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- NATO airstrikes on Yugoslavia have grounded Monica  
Lewinsky's planned book tour in Russia. A Russian publishing house 
has canceled the trip because of Russian opposition to the 
bombings, the Interfax news agency reported. ``One can hardly 
imagine that millions of citizens of Russia would give Ms. Lewinsky 
a proper welcome under the circumstances,'' said a spokeswoman for 
the Russian publishing house Vagrius. Russia staunchly opposes 
NATO's airstrikes on Yugoslavia and there have been protests this 
week at the U.S. and British embassies in Moscow. 

</P>
<P>
	Patrick Roy Ties for Overall Wins  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Patrick Roy tied Jacques Plante for the most  
overall career victories in NHL history with 505 as the Colorado 
Avalanche beat the Washington Capitals 3-1 last night. Roy, who 
finished with 19 saves, has won 406 regular-season games and 99 
playoff games. He is 41 regular-season victories away from Terry 
Sawchuk's NHL record of 447. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
