<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA Tourney Picks Were Just Right </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Let's hear it for the NCAA  
tournament selection committee. They had the field of 64 scoped 
just right. 
</P>
<P>
	For evidence of that, just look at the survivors who arrived in  
Florida for the Final Four. There were three No. 1 seeds -- Duke, 
Connecticut and Michigan State -- and a No. 4 -- Ohio State. And the 
Buckeyes beat the tournament's other No. 1, Auburn, en route to the 
Final Four. 
</P>
<P>
	So after two weekends worth of slam dunks and 3-point shots, the  
field got to just about where the committee thought it would when 
it picked over all those peanuts and pretzels on Selection Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	That's twice in the past three years that three top seeds have  
survived the early rounds, a track record that should quiet 
complaints about how the committee does its work. There are always 
rumbles that some team should have been a 3 instead of a 6, or a 4 
instead of a 9. It's a lot of blather. Take the spot assigned and 
play the games. Win six and you are the national champion. 
</P>
<P>
	The whole idea of seeding is to benefit regular-season and  
conference-tournament achievement. Win games against better 
opponents and the committee notices. Win games on the road and the 
committee notices. Beat a bunch of powderpuffs at home to inflate a 
won-lost record and it notices that, too. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee is locked into conference champions because NCAA  
democracy, sometimes difficult to locate on other issues, dictates 
that the little guys get their chance, too, even if all they seem 
to be is first-round fodder for the powerhouses. 
</P>
<P>
	And that's good because every so often, a Detroit will beat a  
UCLA or a Miami of Ohio will beat a Utah. Nothing against the 
heavyweights, just a neat reminder that other guys can play this 
game, too. 
</P>
<P>
	And sometimes one of those other guys, such as a Southwest  
Missouri State or a Gonzaga, will make it to the late rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The bottom line is that 63 of the teams in this tournament lose  
their final game of the season. That does not make them losers, 
though. There were some substantial winners. 
</P>
<P>
	For starters, try coach Mike Jarvis of St. John's. He had the  
Red Storm a turnover away from the Final Four when freshman point 
guard Erick Barkley bounced a dribble off his leg against Ohio 
State, ending a dream season. 
</P>
<P>
	Barkley was distraught. All season he had been the engine for  
Jarvis' team. Now he was in the locker room, tears in his eyes 
because of that last, critical turnover, the only one he made in 
the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarvis refused to accept that. He talked Barkley through the  
crisis, explaining that without the freshman, St. John's never 
would have been at that juncture. It was a classic coaching moment, 
a lesson in character-building. Once upon a time, that was what 
coaching was supposed to be about. 
</P>
<P>
	John Chaney of Temple would know all about that. He was not  
coaching when Dr. Naismith hung the peach baskets, it just seems 
that way. He went over 600 wins this season, but his most 
significant victory was 6-foot-4 Rasheed Brokenborough. 
</P>
<P>
	Four years after being admitted to Temple as a Proposition 16  
player, forced to sit out his first year because of academic 
issues, Brokenborough is a graduating senior. Now, he is thinking 
about sticking around for his Masters, perhaps petitioning to get 
that year of eligibility back since the courts have ruled against 
the NCAA. 
</P>
<P>
	It seems fair. If redshirts are routinely allowed, permitting  
four years of eligibility over five years, why not extend them to 
academics? Why not reward a player like Brokenborough for his 
accomplishment by giving him that year back? 
</P>
<P>
	As Brokenborough left the court after Temple lost to Duke,  
Chaney hugged the young man. It was a sincere expression of 
affection by an old coach for a young player whose personal 
accomplishment turned that last loss into a much more important 
victory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990327.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 17:22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UConn's Moore Puts Clamps on Penn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- The man known as The Stopper did it  
again. 
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut guard Ricky Moore, a converted scorer and son of a  
PGA Tour caddy, is one of the few players in college basketball 
capable of transforming a game with his defense. 
</P>
<P>
	When it comes to suffocating a team's big scorer and changing  
the flow and tempo of a game, Moore caddies to no one. 
</P>
<P>
	He altered the biggest game in Connecticut history -- one so big  
that virtually the whole state shut down to watch it Saturday -- by 
leaving Ohio State guard Scoonie Penn so off his game that he even 
forgot his own number. 
</P>
<P>
	It's No. 12, by the way, Scoonie, not the No. 35 you brought  
with you to Tropicana Field. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore, called by Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun the best  
defensive player he has coached in 27 years in Division I 
basketball, did what he did best in the NCAA semifinals by limiting 
Penn to 11 points on 3-of-13 shooting in the Huskies' 64-58 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore also scored six points and, despite being just 6-foot-2,  
led the Huskies with eight rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	How good was Moore's defense? Penn was averaging 17.5 points in  
the NCAA tournament and, with teammate Michael Redd, was hailed as 
the best backcourt in the nation. Not now. 
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut (33-2), a team vaunted for its NCAA tournament  
failures, now advances to the first championship game in school 
history against the winner of the Duke-Michigan State game. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a monumental accomplishment for a school that until this  
season had been known for its monumental collapses in March, never 
reaching the Final Four in 20 prior tournaments. 
</P>
<P>
	But then Connecticut has never has had a defender before like  
Moore, who has played a pivotal defensive role throughout the run 
to the NCAA championship game. The game before, he limited Gonzaga 
star Matt Santangelo to 1-of-9 shooting and two points in 29 
minutes, the decisive factor in a 67-62 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	It's nothing new. He held Michigan State's Mateen Cleaves to six  
points on Dec. 5 and Johnny Hemsley of Miami to no second half 
points on Jan. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	There's no `D' in Moore's name, only in his game.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
