<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Awarded $1.78M in Patent Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MISSOULA, Mont. (AP) -- A federal jury has awarded a Bigfork,  
Mont., woman $1.78 million, finding that Deckers Outdoors Corp. 
infringed on the patent for her Yeti cold-weather boots. 
</P>
<P>
	Molly Strong and her company, Yeti by Molly Ltd., won their  
lawsuit in U.S. District Court in Missoula, Mont. 
</P>
<P>
	Deckers, the maker Teva, Ugg and Simple brand footwear, plans to  
appeal the decision, which was handed down last week after a 10-day 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Strong, who is unemployed and lives in a tepee in Bigfork,  
modeled the Yeti after a dog's paw. The soles are large, soft and 
flat, made of fleece and felt to grip on ice and snow. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this decade, she generated some publicity for the boots  
by using them to walk from Denver to Montana. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Strong, 55, contended in her lawsuit that Deckers showed an  
interest in the boot, but worked with her only long enough to copy 
her design as a Teva sandal boot, hiring a former Yeti employee as 
director of product development. 
</P>
<P>
	Deckers, based in Goleta, Calif., claimed that it began making  
the sandal boot in 1992, before the company had met Molly Strong. 
The company quit making the Teva product in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Deckers posted a net loss of $2.9 million on sales of  
$102 million. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
