<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 12:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Williams Sisters Face Off in Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. (AP) -- The first serve of the match came to  
Serena Williams, and she met it with a full swing, rifling a 
forehand crosscourt into the corner for a winner. Opponent Amanda 
Coetzer never moved. 
</P>
<P>
	Venus Williams lunged to her right for an off-balance volley,  
barely reaching the ball to lift a delicate shot that landed softly 
just beyond the net for a winner. Opponent Jana Novotna, frozen 
behind the baseline, could only shake her head. 
</P>
<P>
	With a remarkable combination of finesse and force, the Williams  
sisters have made their way to an all-in-the-family final Sunday at 
the Lipton Championships. Impressed opponents admit the matchup is 
no fluke, but rather a sign of the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their athleticism is incredible,'' said Steffi Graf,  
eliminated by Venus in the semifinals. ``They move extremely well. 
They're taking risks. They go for their shots. They don't have a 
certain weakness. They're very tall and big. That's definitely a 
plus. 
</P>
<P>
	``All those things are definitely working for them.''  
</P>
<P>
	The sisters aren't quite ready to be crowned queens of the WTA  
Tour. Even if Venus wins Sunday, she'll remain ranked No. 6. A 
victory by Serena would boost her to a career-best No. 9. 
</P>
<P>
	They're not necessarily even the best players in their age  
division. Martina Hingis, 18, has five Grand Slam titles to none 
for the Williams sisters. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, the final between Venus, 18, and Serena, 17,  
supports the long-held hunch that they might be destined for 
greatness. 
</P>
<P>
	Serena, who beat Hingis, Coetzer and Monica Seles en route to  
the final, has won 16 consecutive matches and is on the threshold 
of her third tournament title in a row. No longer is she 
overshadowed by Venus, who is 15 months older. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always been in the background,'' Serena said. ``It's time  
for me to move forward now. I'm playing the best tennis I have in 
my young career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Venus has compiled an impressive winning streak, too -- 11  
matches in a row at Lipton, including last year's final and 
victories this week over Graf and Novotna. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like putting my name and losing in the same  
sentence,'' Venus said. ``Winning and Venus sounds great. Serena 
doesn't like to lose either.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last all-sibling final in professional tennis was in 1991,  
when John McEnroe beat his brother Patrick at Chicago. Williams vs. 
Williams will be the first all-sister women's final since the Open 
era began in 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	The sisters don't seem as impressed by the achievement as the  
international media. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporter: ``Would you say a new era has arrived in women's  
tennis as of this week?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Venus: ``I guess so. It could be said.''  
</P>
<P>
	Reporter: ``Would you say it?''  
</P>
<P>
	Venus: ``I could say it, yes: A new era has arrived this week in  
women's tennis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The scale of the occasion is such that their father, Richard,  
held a news conference Saturday. Prone to hyperbole, he bragged 
about various family medical and law degrees, Venus' fluency in 
four languages and his role in a group that may buy Rockefeller 
Center for $3.9 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	But there was no exaggeration in the pride he expressed for  
Sunday's finalists. 
</P>
<P>
	``My only hope in watching my babies is that I don't cry,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The sisters practiced together Saturday, joking about mishit  
overheads and still laughing when they left the court. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're saying, `I'm going to hit the ball sister -- you'd  
better be ready,' '' their dad said. 
</P>
<P>
	Venus is 2-0 against Serena, with both matches last year. They  
played each other for the first time at the Australian Open in 
January, then at the Italian Open in May. 
</P>
<P>
	When they played each other as children, Venus usually won.  
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah,'' she said. ``But that's in the past.''  
</P>
<P>
	The future arrives Sunday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
