<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suit Filed in `Angel of Death' Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A respiratory therapist who confessed to  
killing dozens of hospital patients but then recanted has been sued 
by the family of a man who died while the therapist was on duty. 
</P>
<P>
	The Superior Court lawsuit against Efren Saldivar was filed  
Friday by the estate and heirs of John N. Schwartz, an elderly man 
who died at the Glendale Adventist Medical Center hospital on May 
31, 1993. It claims wrongful death and negligent infliction of 
emotional distress upon the family. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit also names the hospital. It is the first suit filed in  
the so-called ``Angel of Death'' case, which has not resulted in 
any charges against Salvidar. He has, however, been fired from the 
hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Saldivar confessed to killing patients between  
1989 and 1997 who looked ``like they were ready to die'' by 
suffocating them or giving them lethal injections. 
</P>
<P>
	He later recanted.  
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that Mr. Schwartz was a victim of Efren Saldivar,''  
the family's lawyer, Christopher Nicoll said. ``There were many 
suspicious circumstances surrounding his death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saldivar, 29, was on duty when 91-year-old man died ``and there  
were apparently no other persons present at the time of Mr. 
Schwartz's untimely death,'' the suit said. 
</P>
<P>
	The amount of general and punitive damages being sought wasn't  
specified. The whereabouts of Saldivar were not known. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no comment from the hospital, which hadn't seen the  
lawsuit, spokeswoman Alicia Gonzalez said. 
</P>
<P>
	Glendale police Sgt. Rick Young said detectives are still  
investigating the case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
