<DOCNO> APW19990327.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 15:09:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Divided on Airstrikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Several days into the bombing, Americans  
remained closely divided on the wisdom of the military action 
against Yugoslavia, new polls have found. Narrow majorities backed 
the effort but opinion was unsettled, with the prospect of American 
casualties a worry. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton's handling of the crisis won support in a  
variety of polls, although the edge was slight, and it appeared he 
was persuading more Americans that military intervention was the 
right course. 
</P>
<P>
	Support for U.S. involvement in the air campaign stood at 53  
percent in a Newsweek poll taken during the second and third days 
of the bombing, which began Wednesday. Thirty-six percent opposed 
it. A Time-CNN poll found 44 percent approving of the action and 40 
percent against it. 
</P>
<P>
	A rise in support was sharply noted in an ABC News poll taken  
Friday in which 60 percent approved of the strikes, up from 47 per 
cent on the eve of the campaign. Less dramatically, support stood 
at 50 percent or a bit better in polls by CBS News, USA 
Today-Gallup and the Los Angeles Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Indicating just how tentative opinion is on the U.S. course in  
the Balkans, no more than 3 or 4 percentage points -- the margins of 
error in most of the surveys -- separated opposing views on many key 
questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Although NATO reported no causalities or losses of its  
warplanes, the danger of the operation was high on people's minds. 
More respondents than not in the Newsweek poll predicted NATO 
casualties and in the ABC survey, 49 percent said peace in Kosovo 
is not worth the loss of U.S. lives while 45 percent said it would 
be. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked by Time and CNN how many American lives ``would you be  
willing to sacrifice to achieve U.S. goals'' in Kosovo, 74 percent 
said none while 14 percent said fewer than 100. 
</P>
<P>
	Newsweek found Clinton's overall approval rating dropped to 57  
percent from 63 percent early in the month, indicating the public 
may not be rallying around him as vigorously as they often do for 
presidents in the opening of a military campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	A slight majority in the ABC survey say he has not done enough  
to explain the need for U.S. involvement. Still, more approved of 
his handling of the situation than not, even while a majority did 
not believe vital U.S. interests are at stake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
