<DOCNO> APW19990327.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 05:41:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DiMaggio Jersey Sold for $56,025 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bob Payne was in an orphanage in Winston Salem,  
N.C., in 1955 when he was given a Mickey Mantle jersey from a crate 
of items donated by the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	The pinstriped jersey had been worn by Mantle in 1952, his first  
full season in the big leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	Payne decided it finally was time to part with that cherished  
No. 7 jersey, and it was auctioned this week along with other 
memorabilia at Leland's auction house in New York. It fetched 
$42,093. 
</P>
<P>
	Even more valuable was a road uniform jersey worn by Joe  
DiMaggio in 1939, his first full season with the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	That jersey went for $56,025. It was held by the same family  
since 1940. The man who offered it to Leland's for auction got it 
from his father who played on semi-pro team in New Jersey, and 
received the jersey because he was the star of the squad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990327.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 02:11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                       *Viacheslav Chornovil    	
</P>
<P>
	KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- Viacheslav Chornovil, one of Ukraine's most  
prominent politicians and a former Soviet political prisoner, died 
Thursday in a car crash. He was 61. 
</P>
<P>
	Chornovil, the longtime leader of the opposition Popular Rukh  
movement and a key figure in Ukraine's fight for independence from 
the Soviet Union, was killed when his car collided with a truck 
near the capital, Kiev. 
</P>
<P>
	Chornovil worked as a journalist, became active in the Soviet  
human rights movement and was ousted from a newspaper in 1966 for 
refusing to testify at a political trial. 
</P>
<P>
	He was arrested in 1967 for his dissident activities and  
sentenced to three years in prison, a term later cut in half. In 
1972 he was again arrested, this time as publisher of an 
underground newsletter, and sentenced to six years in prison and 
three years in exile. 
</P>
<P>
	He served his term in exile in Siberia.  
</P>
<P>
	In April 1980, Communist authorities again sentenced Chornovil  
to five years in prison, but he was released in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	In the late 1980s he became the leading advocate of Ukrainian  
independence and was instrumental in forming the pro-independence 
Popular Rukh in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Chornovil ran for Ukraine's presidency in 1991, but finished  
second. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Albert Gollin    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Albert Gollin, a renowned researcher at Columbia  
University and the American Newspaper Publishers Association, died 
Wednesday. He was 68. 
</P>
<P>
	Gollin directed public opinion surveys at Columbia University's  
Bureau of Applied Social Research and Washington's Bureau of Social 
Science Research during the 1960s and 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of his work centered on civil rights, poverty issues and  
the protest movements of the time. He later went on to become a 
research leader on newspapers and their audiences at the American 
Newspaper Publishers Association. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, Gollin was awarded the distinguished achievement award  
from the American Association for Public Opinion Research. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, Ann; two children and three  
stepchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Sonny Hirsch    	
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Sonny Hirsch, a broadcaster for the University of  
Miami for nearly 30 years, died Thursday of an apparent heart 
attack at 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Hirsch did play-by-play of Miami football, basketball and  
baseball games from 1958 to 1971 and again from 1983 to 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Hirsch also hosted sportscasts and sports talk shows. He was  
inducted into the University of Miami Hall of Fame a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	He was an official scorer at Florida Marlins games since their  
first season in 1993. 

</P>
<P>
                      *Bobbye Hughes McDermott    	
</P>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- Bobbye Hughes McDermott, founder of Honolulu's  
oldest and largest public relations firm, died Tuesday of cancer. 
She was 71. 
</P>
<P>
	McDermott came to Hawaii in 1958 and worked for several top  
advertising and public relations agencies before founding 
Communications Pacific in 1969. The firm handled accounts such as 
the Mauna Kea Beach Hotel on the Big Island and the Hawaii 
Independent Refinery on Oahu. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, she was inducted into the Public Relations Society of  
America Hall of Honor. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Arthur E. Raymond    	
</P>
<P>
	SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Arthur E. Raymond, a Douglas  
Aircraft engineer who was a key figure in designing the DC-3 
transport plane and a founder of the Rand think tank, died Monday 
at age 99. 
</P>
<P>
	Raymond was working for Douglas Aircraft in 1932 when he became  
lead designer of the DC-1, the prototype of the twin-engine DC-3. 
An improved model, the DC-2, went into production, and the DC-3 
came out in 1935. At that time, the DC-3 was a major advance in 
passenger comfort. 
</P>
<P>
	During his 35 years with Douglas, Raymond was involved with a  
variety of projects, including the DC-8 commercial jetliner and 
antiaircraft missiles that were placed around major cities during 
the 1950s. 
</P>
<P>
	After retiring as vice president for engineering in 1960, he  
became a consultant to Rand and an adviser to the Apollo space 
program. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Dorin Teodorescu    	
</P>
<P>
	BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) -- Dorin Teodorescu, an acclaimed  
Romanian tenor who played leading roles in hundreds of operetta 
shows, died Friday following brain surgery. He was 56. 
</P>
<P>
	Teodorescu, who was director of Bucharest's Ion Dacian Operetta  
company, had suffered a stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	Teodorescu graduated from Romania's music conservatory in 1965  
and immediately became his countrymen's operetta idol. 
</P>
<P>
	He played lead roles in works by Johann Strauss and Franz Lehar  
on various European stages and in Tel Aviv, Israel. He also gave 
concerts with arias from operas by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, Giacomo 
Puccini and others. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Anthony Yturri    	
</P>
<P>
	ONTARIO, Ore. (AP) -- Anthony Yturri, a four-term state senator  
once recognized as the dean of Oregon Republicans, died Tuesday at 
age 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Yturri was elected to the Senate in 1956 and also served as  
chairman of the Oregon Transportation Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	He also served on several corporate boards including the U.S.  
National Bank of Oregon, Union Pacific Railroad and Equitable 
Savings &AMP; Loan Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Yturri, who began his career practicing law in Ontario in 1937,  
served on the Senate Transportation Committee throughout his Senate 
career. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Doug Edelson    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Radio journalist Doug Edelson, whose  
characteristic deep voice and political interviews were broadcast 
for more than a quarter of a century on WINS, has died. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	Edelson died Friday at a hospital in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. He  
had been hospitalized since Sunday after suffering a heart attack, 
his family said. 
</P>
<P>
	Edelson had interviewed every president from Harry Truman to  
George Bush, ``and put his stamp on New York's biggest news 
events,'' the station said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since his retirement five years ago, Edelson lived in Florida  
and Pennsylvania with his wife, Barbara. 
</P>
<P>
	Edelson is survived by his wife; twin daughters, Jeanne Edelson  
and Catherine Fischer; and a grandson, Matthew Douglas Verlaque. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Lawrence Duke Sr.    	
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Lawrence ``Dan'' Duke Sr., the former chief judge  
of the State Court of Fulton County who once waved a whip in the 
face of former Gov. Eugene Talmadge to prove a point about racism, 
has died. He was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke who was known for his work defending blacks and prosecuting  
those who carried out racially charged crimes, died Wednesday of 
pneumonia at Fayette Community Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke was best known for his confrontation with Talmadge in 1941.  
As an assistant solicitor for the state, Duke successfully 
convicted several members of the Ku Klux Klann for the flogging 
death of a black man. 
</P>
<P>
	After Talmadge threatened to grant the men clemency, Duke waved  
the whips used in the crime in the governor's face. Talmadge 
relented. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include Mrs. Fletcher, sons Lawrence Duke Barnes of  
Denver, Daniel Duke Jr. of Alpharetta, and Tarleton C. Duke of 
Tyrone; sister Myra Duke Coulon of Barnesville; and four 
grandchildren. 

</P>
