<DOCNO> APW19990327.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 15:12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Looks To Buy Part of Hornets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Michael Jordan isn't finished with the  
NBA. Barely two months after retiring as a player, Jordan is 
working on a deal to rejoin the league as a part owner of the 
Charlotte Hornets. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials with the NBA and the Hornets confirmed Saturday that  
Jordan began speaking with team owner George Shinn earlier this 
month about buying a 50-percent share of the franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been preliminary discussions about Michael and  
George becoming equal partners in the ownership and operation of 
the Hornets,'' NBA commissioner David Stern said in a statement 
released by the league Saturday. ``Those discussions are ongoing 
but are not near an agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shinn, who brought pro basketball to Charlotte 11 years ago but  
has fallen on hard times lately, also released a statement saying 
he was hopeful of completing a deal with Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been preliminary discussions about Michael Jordan  
possibly becoming an ownership partner with me,'' Shinn said. ``Our 
hope over the next few meetings is to work out a partnership that 
will benefit the Hornets and the entire community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hornets officials said no firm dates had been set for the two  
sides to meet again, but that both parties had agreed to stay in 
touch over the coming weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan, who retired from the Chicago Bulls in January, could not  
be located for comment Saturday, and his agent, David Falk, did not 
return telephone messages left at his home. 
</P>
<P>
	The Charlotte Observer first reported Saturday that Jordan was  
interested in buying a share of the Hornets. Such a deal would not 
only return Jordan to the game he helped shape over the past 13 
years, but it would give a boost to a franchise that has been under 
fire for poor leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's some uncertainty because there could be an ownership  
change, but by and large everyone's pretty excited,'' said a 
Hornets employee who spoke to The Associated Press on the condition 
of anonymity. ``This could work out great for everybody. This could 
help George solve his image problem, give Michael something to do 
in retirement and give the team a boost at the same time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan is the only potential buyer now in negotiations with  
Shinn, The Observer reported, citing a source it said was close to 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Shinn was granted an expansion franchise for $32.5 million and  
was revered in Charlotte when the Hornets made their debut in 1988. 
Now, however, he is viewed by fans as someone unwilling to pay the 
big money needed to keep top talent, and there have been calls for 
him to sell the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Dave Cowens resigned in frustration this month, and fans  
have been demonstrating their displeasure with the state of the 
team by not showing up for games. Turnstile counts have dropped 
considerably in the past year at the 23,799-seat Charlotte 
Coliseum, which used to be among the NBA leaders in attendance. 
</P>
<P>
	Shinn, who counters his detractors by saying he needs a new  
arena to generate the money needed to pay the best players, also 
has personal problems. His wife has filed for divorce, and several 
women have accused him of sexual misconduct, including one who has 
named him as a defendant in a lawsuit in South Carolina, where 
Shinn has a home. 
</P>
<P>
	Into the mix steps Jordan and his six NBA championships, five  
MVP awards, 10 scoring titles and unsurpassed worldwide fame. 
</P>
<P>
	When Jordan retired as a player for the first time in 1993, he  
briefly pursued a professional baseball career before returning to 
the NBA late in the 1994-95 season. When he retired this year, he 
said he wanted to devote more time to his wife and three children, 
play more golf and focus on his various business interests. 
</P>
<P>
	Those business activities have helped him generate an annual  
off-court income estimated at $45 million, which would enable him 
to afford a piece of an NBA franchise said to be worth at least 
$150 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Buying into the Hornets also would draw Jordan closer to his  
childhood roots. Raised in Wilmington, N.C., Jordan played for 
North Carolina, and his mother lives in Charlotte. He already has 
several business interests in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a great thing to have Jordan come in, but there's  
still the question of where Shinn fits in the picture,'' said D.J. 
Wittek, a patron of the Selwyn Avenue Pub, a popular postgame 
eatery. ``I think a lot of people will wonder how long a 50-50 
thing between Shinn and Jordan can last.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bulls owner Jerry Reinsdorf said he wasn't surprised at word  
that Jordan could join the ranks of NBA owners. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know that it's going to happen. But no, nothing  
surprises me about Michael,'' Reinsdorf said in Mesa, Ariz., where 
he was attending spring training for his Chicago White Sox. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
