<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rapist Terrorizes Atlanta Suburbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SMYRNA, Ga. (AP) -- Women in the suburbs north of Atlanta jog  
through their neatly landscaped neighborhoods only in pairs these 
days, and many pack more than water bottles. At night, they 
barricade doors and sleep with kitchen knives or even machetes 
beside their beds. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past six months, 24 woman have been attacked,  
apparently by the same man. All the women -- some alone, some with 
male companions -- were robbed, five were raped and at least five 
others suffered some form of sexual assault. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are taking it very seriously,'' said Kathy Fitzner, 45,  
who lives two buildings away from where one woman was attacked. ``I 
had some Mace but I never carried it. Now I've got that, a siren 
attached to my bed and a cell phone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police won't say if they have DNA or other evidence linking the  
crimes, which began in October, but they say victims' descriptions, 
crime locations and times, and the man's tactics have been similar. 
The attacker sometimes wears a ski mask or cap and dark clothing. 
</P>
<P>
	Police also say he carries a silver-colored handgun.  
</P>
<P>
	But he has only used the gun once, in the latest attack. The  
victim was shot in the side when she opened the door after a man 
knocked to tell her she left her headlights on. The 33-year-old 
woman, who was not sexually assaulted, has been released from a 
hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``It shows that he's escalating,'' Fulton County police Maj.  
Terry Mulkey said. ``This person is displaying very violent 
tendencies now and it does alarm us and it should alarm the 
community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All the crimes have been in Cobb, DeKalb and Fulton counties,  
within a couple of miles of Interstate 285. Besides the separate 
county investigations, the FBI and the Georgia Bureau of 
Investigation are looking into the crime wave and helping with a 
profile of the attacker, Mulkey said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Although robbery appears to be the primary motive, the man  
sexually assaults his victims whenever circumstances permit, said 
Cobb County police spokesman Robert Quigley. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the women were accosted in a parking lot as they walked  
to or from their residences. Some attacks took place at restaurants 
or shopping malls. 
</P>
<P>
	``My son came over and brought two guns and told us to pick  
one,'' said Jessie Ford, 68, who lives with her husband at a Cobb 
County complex. ``I never did like guns and we never had one, but I 
tell ya', when something like this happens ...'' 
</P>
<P>
	The location of the attacks have run the gamut from older  
complexes with several entrances to new apartment complexes with 
iron gates accessible only with a remote or code number. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been two rapes since December at the Waterford Place  
apartments in Fulton County. 
</P>
<P>
	Resident Barbara Bretas, 21, isn't taking any chances. When she  
returned home late one night, the Georgia State student saw an 
unfamiliar man in the parking lot. 
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as I got out of my car I just started screaming and  
ran to my apartment and opened my door really fast and got in,'' 
she said. ``When I looked out the window he was still there so I 
called 911. Five minutes later, there were like four police cars 
here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The man was apparently just a visitor and not arrested.  
</P>
<P>
	Most of the communities in the area have distributed fliers with  
the police sketch. In many, police have met with residents to 
discuss the investigation and safety measures. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents are being advised to avoid going outside at night  
alone and to carry a whistle or pepper spray. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's still no substitute for common sense -- looking around  
when getting in and out of your car, looking in the shadows,'' 
Mulkey said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
