<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dr. Charged in Mayo Clinic Theft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- A Japanese doctor completing a research  
fellowship at the Mayo Clinic was charged with stealing medical 
research data from the clinic. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Yoichi Ito of Osaka appeared before U.S. Magistrate Judge  
John Mason late Friday afternoon. He was ordered not to travel 
outside Minnesota and to return to court Wednesday, or else face a 
$25,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	According to an FBI search warrant affidavit filed Thursday,  
Ito, 32, had been working in Mayo's cartilage and connective tissue 
laboratory in Rochester. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he was warned when he arrived in 1997 that his research  
work belonged to the clinic, Mayo officials discovered last week 
that he had removed his own notes and research materials from the 
clinic and stolen other research data from clinic computers, the 
affidavit said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Mayo spokesman said Ito was to have completed a two-year  
fellowship in the orthopedic research department on Monday, the end 
of the academic quarter. He was scheduled to return to Japan that 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	Ito declined to comment after his release.  
</P>
<P>
	According to the affidavit, Ito had been working on gene  
sequencing research associated with the laboratory's efforts to 
synthesize genes and cells that might allow a human body to 
regenerate and replace diseased or damaged cartilage and connective 
tissue. 
</P>
<P>
	He is accused of downloading lab research dating to 1990 from  
the lab's computer onto optical disks without authorization, as 
well as illegally removing slides and research materials produced 
by others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
