<HEADLINE> Lonesome Glory Wins Carolina Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMDEN, S.C. (AP) -- Lonesome Glory, a four-time Eclipse Award  
winner, showed age is no deterrent to success, drawing off to 
victory in Saturday's $100,000 Carolina Cup steeplechase. 
</P>
<P>
	The 11-year-old Lonesome Glory drew even with leader Assurance  
at the 14th and final fence and cruised a 6 3/4-length victory at 
Springdale Race Course before a National Steeplechase Association 
record crowd of 69,300. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner topped a field of six, traveling the 2 1/4-mile course  
in 4:22 4-5 with Blythe Miller aboard. Lonesome Glory is trained by 
Miller's father, Bruce, and owned by Kay Jeffords. 
</P>
<P>
	Assurance, who held on for second, set the pace for Saturday's  
feature. He grabbed the lead at the first fence and held until 
Lonesome Glory blew by at the end. 
</P>
<P>
	Assurance was 1 1/4 lengths ahead of Romantic.  
</P>
<P>
	Rowdy Irishman and Fifth Creek rounded out the finishers. Prime  
Legacy was eased before the final fence. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a happy return to Springdale for Lonesome Glory in his  
first start of the year. The champion won the Carolina Cup in 1997 
and also owns three Colonial Cups, the steeplechase race run here 
each fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Blythe Miller said that her horse took her to the front at the  
right time after biding his time in the middle of the pack most of 
the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was confident that my horse had enough to get home,'' she  
said. ``He just had to get going. He's got class. He ran a great 
race today. It was great to see him run like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Augustin Stables' Henares won the $35,000 Woodward-Kirkover Cup,  
the co-feature on the six-race card. Henares was ridden by Craig 
Thornton and trained by Sanna Neilson. 
</P>
<P>
	Thornton and Neilson also won the $25,000 Springdale Cup with  
Augustin Stables' Brankman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
