<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 09:41:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Golfers Say TPC Course Too Tough  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- The greens are too brown. The  
rough is too thick. The fairways aren't fair. The whole course is 
sick. 
</P>
<P>
	With years of practice, PGA professionals have transformed the  
art of complaining about golf courses into pure poetry. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the incessant carping this week at The Players  
Championship has stood out -- and cast a pall over the tournament 
that nobody can seem to escape. 
</P>
<P>
	Naturally, the worse the score, the more unhappy the player. Yet  
even the leaders had strong comments about the Stadium Course on 
the TPC at Sawgrass, a par-72 layout that played at an average of 
2.1 strokes over par over the first two days. 
</P>
<P>
	If this keeps up, only the U.S. and British Opens will have  
played tougher over the past year. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't make everybody happy,'' said Davis Love III, a  
player-director on the PGA Tour Policy Board. ``This is major 
championship golf conditions that you see just a few times a year. 
A lot of guys aren't used to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not that anybody could ever become accustomed to 6-inch rough  
around the greens and fairways. 
</P>
<P>
	It was so bad that Brandt Jobe chose to hit off a cart path  
instead of taking a drop into the thick grass after an errant drive 
at No. 18 Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	During Friday's round, Tiger Woods hacked a ball out of rough so  
thick it literally sent him spinning through his follow-through, a 
la Babe Ruth after a swinging third strike. 
</P>
<P>
	First-round co-leader Bob Estes missed one fairway and it took  
the spotter three minutes to find his ball, even though it landed 
only five feet to his right. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you miss a green, you are chipping out of however long  
rough they want to call it, five or six inches,'' David Duval said. 
``You have to take a good swing to hit, but at the same time try 
not to progress the ball. That combination doesn't work. That is 
what makes it so difficult.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the rest of the complaints have to do with the greens.  
</P>
<P>
	In no particular order, players are upset because they feel they  
are running too fast, the pin placements are too difficult and they 
are dying out and look terrible on TV. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like it as far as aesthetics,'' said Fuzzy Zoeller,  
who missed the cut with a score of 11-over 155. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looked (bad) on TV yesterday. This is someplace we're  
supposed to be promoting as our TPC course, and there I see brown 
greens. You get that at Amelia golf course.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What you won't find there are pin placements that can make a  
good shot look bad. Woods and Curtis Strange were among those who 
couldn't believe the difficulty of the placements so early in the 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``On 13, it's 1 1/2 steps from falling off the ridge,'' Woods said.  
``That's not right. You can lip out a putt and run it off the 
ridge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Strange: ``You can grow rough and have narrow fairways, but  
have the greens the way they normally are. Within reason, you can 
speed them up. But don't have the pin right to the edge. Just use 
good judgment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past few years, managers at TPC have made a concerted  
effort to toughen the course, hoping to avoid a replay of Greg 
Norman's winning score of 24 under in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, the challenge has been to find a happy medium.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is our tournament. We should have some say in it,  
shouldn't we?'' Ernie Els said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody wants to turn it into the U.S. Open, where Lee Janzen won  
with a score of even par at The Olympic Club in San Francisco last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Then again, this tournament has drawn the third-best field of  
the decade. Everyone agrees they should leave having felt properly 
challenged. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is our Players Championship and we should be able to put  
out the absolute best golf course available to us,'' Zoeller said. 
``I think they've gone overboard with it, but ... Someone's going 
to win Sunday and be very happy with it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
