<DOCNO> APW19990327.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 12:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  US Teen Skater Last but Has Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELSINKI, Finland (AP) - For a 13-year-old figure skater who was  
not supposed to be at the World Championships, Sarah Hughes had a 
great time. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes nailed six triples to finish sixth in the free skating  
and seventh overall as Maria Butyrskaya of Russia beat out American 
Michelle Kwan for the title. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a blast out there. It was so much fun,'' she said. ``I'm  
just so happy. Being here is so great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The skater from Great Neck, N.Y., was ninth after the short  
program. 
</P>
<P>
	She skated to ``Swan Lake'' in the long program Saturday, not  
making any major mistakes and even doing two triple lutzes 
including one in combination. 
</P>
<P>
	She received marks from 5.2 up to 5.6, and finished ahead of the  
other American, Angela Nikodinov, who came in 12th. Hughes was 
ecstatic coming off the ice and hugged her coach Robin Wagner. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes finished fourth in the U.S. championships in February  
with only three women's spots available. 
</P>
<P>
	Another 13-year-old, Naomi Nari Nam, was second to Kwan but was  
not allowed on the team, being below the minimum age limit of 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, Hughes was picked because of a special exception  
that allows junior worlds medalists to participate in the senior 
worlds. Hughes was second in the world junior championships in 
December. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't do anything about the rules ... I just wanted to do my  
best and not worry,'' Hughes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes was the youngest competitor in Helsinki. She said she  
didn't let her age worry her. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't really think about it. I just wanted to show I could  
do well here, that I belong here,'' Hughes said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990327.0144 </DOCNO>
